<FIRST>r a PM-NewsChoppers     11-28 0987</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-News Choppers,1015</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot-Reporters, Authorities Fight For Space Over News Sites</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FELIX GUTIERREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A helicopter flying in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> last summer only wanted to shoot film for NBC News, but a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> destroyer almost blew it out of the sky when the crew failed to respond to repeated warnings. News helicopters around the world are becoming more aggressive in their quest for the best pictures. Pilots and officials now are taking steps to avoid disaster, to strike a balance between the First Amendment and public safety. Following last May's $ 7-million <LOCATION> Redondo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> pier fire near <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, news pilot <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Tur </PERSON> was criticized for fanning smoke and flames, endangering firefighters, and hampering radio communications with noise. `` We can be a pain,'' acknowledged Tur, who is currently appealing a 180-day license suspension for an unrelated infraction. But he denied he hovered too close, and said that was n't the real reason for his problems. `` People sometimes do n't want publicity. But if the media did n't tell you, who would?'' More news choppers are buzzing the skies above big news events, from earthquakes to chemical spills. Often, it's the only way television crews or newspaper photographers can grab pictures of a distant sea rescue or landslide before deadline. Not too long ago, only the three major television stations in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> used helicopters, said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Dreesman </PERSON>, whose <ORGANIZATION> Helitac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> currently flies for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> and other news organizations. Nowadays, photographers from such publications as the National Enquirer spend hours each week airborne. `` We ask -LRB- the news helicopters -RRB- to back off and most of them are pretty polite about it,'' said Sgt. <PERSON> Brent </PERSON> <PERSON> Carey </PERSON> of the police Air Support Division. `` Others are pretty persistent. They want to keep taking their pictures and at times it becomes an annoyance.'' These days, teamwork among helicopters begins to play a more important role _ and that's not the most common trait in such a competitive business. `` There's no problem in and around a major event when pilots communicate,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Pettee </PERSON>, who flies for <ORGANIZATION> KNBC-TV </ORGANIZATION>. `` The only problem is when somebody does something unexpected.'' <PERSON> Pettee </PERSON> said experienced news pilots can shoot a chemical spill without stirring up toxic gas, stay far enough away from a hostage situation to avoid exciting a gunman, and cooperate with other pilots on the scene. Sometimes they even help officials by tracking fires or flying out victims, he said. Complaints were common before the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> limited flights around disasters in 1985, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Joann </PERSON> <PERSON> Sloan </PERSON> said. The restrictions allow local officials to ask the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> to declare fires, crashes and other incidents off-limits to aircraft for safety reasons. News aircraft are permitted only if they file a flight plan, fly above rescue aircraft, obey on-site authorities, and follow other rules. <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> fire and law enforcement officials said they coordinate coverage with news helicopters as they show up on the scene. `` I think the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> thinks they have things under control,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Sloan </PERSON>. `` We have n't had any disasters occur with these -LRB- news -RRB- helicopters that I know of anytime recently.'' But last December <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON>, then-Chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, cited helicopter problems in asking the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> to tighten controls around disaster sites. <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON> cited six incidents since 1974 where news helicopters worsened hazards or hampered rescue efforts. These included stirring up fumes and dust around spills of hazardous materials, a fatal crash over a chemical fire, and distracting ground rescue crews. `` These incidents illustrate how non-rescue aircraft can interfere with rescue and clean-up activities and endanger the lives and health of the occupants of the aircraft, the victims of the accident, and the emergency response personnel responding to the fire or hazardous materials incident,'' <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON> wrote. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> declined to issue new rules in March, but he pledged the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> would impose a 180-day license suspension for pilots ignoring flight restrictions. Tur knows all about such suspensions. The pilot, whose company sells videotape to several television stations, ran into trouble with federal officials in March 1987 over the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> jet fighter crash that killed <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, son of entertainer <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> honored a request by search officials to issue flight restrictions around the crash site in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> east of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, according to testimony at a suspension hearing last September. Tur was warned away from the area by an <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> colonel on the scene. But he flew by to shoot late afternoon pictures of searchers combing the steep, brush-filled mountainside for debris and bodies. Other news crews were escorted over the scene at a higher altitude. Tur contended that flights were restricted only to avoid publicity. `` Never can a local, state, or federal agency prevent news media representatives from flying into an area because public relations does n't want the story told,'' he said. But Col. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cross </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> officer at the site, testified news helicopters posed a safety threat. He said <PERSON> Tur </PERSON>'s noisy flight `` significantly disrupted my coordination efforts'' by distracting searchers, and jeopardized their safety Like Tur, the late <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Galanis </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> KUSA-TV </ORGANIZATION>, who was head of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, felt the <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> crash site was restricted merely to curb publicity. `` I think it's obvious if it was not <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>'s son there would not have been a -LRB- restriction -RRB- in effect,'' <PERSON> Galanis </PERSON> said in an interview a few weeks before his own death in a helicopter crash. <PERSON> Galanis </PERSON> and cameraman <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Hostetler </PERSON> were returning from covering a plane crash Oct. 19 when their helicopter became entangled in a utility cable and crashed southwest of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. Both men were killed. Blocking or limiting media helicopters, <PERSON> Galanis </PERSON> said in the interview, `` prevents the public from seeing events that they're entitled to see under the First Amendment.
