<SECOND>PM-Litterbug Buster,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Columnist Fights Litterbugs; Gets Six Stitches</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A newspaper columnist's beef about litterbugs got him into trouble on the city streets he's trying to keep clean. A few weeks ago, The <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inquirer </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> <PERSON> DeLeon </PERSON> wrote a column criticizing litterbugs and criticizing himself for not standing up to them. He swore, in print, that next time he saw a litterbug, he would say something. He got his opportunity Saturday, along with six stitches for his effort. <PERSON> DeLeon </PERSON>, in his column Monday, wrote he and his wife were driving in the city when they saw four teen-agers throw two large beverage containers out of a car with <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> license plates. <PERSON> DeLeon </PERSON> got out of his car, picked up the containers and gave them back to the driver, saying, `` Do me a favor, pal, take these back to <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> with you.'' About a block later, while both cars were stuck in traffic, three teen-agers from the other car ran up to <PERSON> DeLeon </PERSON>'s. When <PERSON> DeLeon </PERSON> got out, he said, one `` whacked'' him from behind before they fled. <PERSON> DeLeon </PERSON> said he received six stitches about an inch below his right eye, where his glasses dug into his cheekbone when he was hit. He wrote that the doctor in the emergency room congratulated him for `` doing what she has often wanted to do but has been afraid to do for reasons that were as clear as the face in front of her.''
