<FIRST>r i PM-DisfiguredSoldier     11-29 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Disfigured Soldier,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maimed Soldier Appeals To Countrymen For Consideration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A young reserve soldier whose face was burned and mutilated by a firebomb went on television to ask fellow Israelis to show some understanding and stop staring at him. <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Navon </PERSON>, a 25-year-old university student, was doing his required duty in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> last June when Palestinians hurled a firebomb at his jeep. His face was disfigured and all his fingers had to be amputated. He decided to appear on an Israeli TV talk show Monday night, he said, because his countrymen react so cruelly when they encounter victims like himself in public. `` All the stares lock on you,'' he said. `` Sometimes it's helplessness, or even fear ... People just have no tact and they shout things, like, ` Look at this weirdo, look at this creature!' `` As though we are not living in a country where people should know about this phenomenom. It happens a lot and I'm not the only one; there are a lot like me.'' <PERSON> Navon </PERSON>'s entire face is covered with burns and scar tissue. His ears were burned off. His fingerless hands are still wrapped in bandages. He appeared on TV with his girlfriend, <PERSON> Miri </PERSON> <PERSON> Amiel </PERSON>. They began dating about six months before he was hurt, and Ms. <PERSON> Amiel </PERSON> said they were closer now than ever. `` Before, we were like any couple, going out together, studying together, having fun. ... Now we have to deal with all these things together,'' she said. `` Of course, <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> has to deal with it more than I, but I am a partner in everything.'' They met at college, where he was taking a preparatory course before studying for a degree. <PERSON> Amiel </PERSON> said she, too, is pained by the public's reaction. `` It's very sad for me ... to see all the stares, and hope that <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> does n't notice,'' she said. Tragedy struck <PERSON> Navon </PERSON> at 11 p.m. on June 14, the last day of his unit's 24-day tour of duty in the occupied areas. His jeep entered <LOCATION> Beit </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Umar </LOCATION> village for one last patrol before returning to base for a farewell party. `` I did n't want to do the extra round because it was late,'' he said. `` I felt a ... strange feeling. ... After a moment or two I felt the Molotov cocktail. All of me was burning. ... I could n't open the door to get out of the jeep. Since then, <PERSON> Navon </PERSON> has undergone more than a dozen operations and skin transplants. He said he began crying when he realized what he looked like and `` my brother and my girlfriend ... also started crying. ... A few minutes later I said, O.K., guys, calm down, everything will be all right, this is n't going to break me.'' The television showed a photograph of <PERSON> Navon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Amiel </PERSON>, taken before the attack and portraying a handsome young man in army uniform. `` I was always a pretty realistic and rational type,'' <PERSON> Navon </PERSON> said. `` This new situation is not simple and not easy ... but it wo n't help to complain or ask why I look like this.'' He said he was appealing to Israeli society to be kinder to burn victims not for himself but because other burn victims were more sensitive than he. At least 10 people have suffered serious burns in firebomb attacks in the past year _ a frequent weapon in the yearlong <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> uprising that has killed more than 300 Palestinians and 11 Israelis. <PERSON> Navon </PERSON> said he harbors no desire for revenge and no feelings of hatred toward the Palestinians who attacked him. He said Palestinian insurrectionists have `` a struggle of their own, and the way they're doing it, with violence, they wo n't accomplish anything They must sit and talk this problem out.''
</TEXT>
