<HEAD>Service Station Mistakenly Sells Gasoline-Tainted Kerosene</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police used loudspeakers and flyers Monday to warn residents about a dangerous mixture of gas and kerosene that mistakenly was sold for use in space heaters. The fuel could cause fire or explosion if used in heating devices, Lt. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Boggs </PERSON> said. `` We've got squad cars going up and down streets in two police districts using their public address systems to warn people, and officers are handing out flyers to people on the street,'' <PERSON> Boggs </PERSON> said. `` We're also getting very good cooperation from radio and television stations,'' he said. On Saturday, a fuel company delivered gas to a <ORGANIZATION> Martin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> service station, but mistakenly poured 1,640 gallons into a kerosene tank, <PERSON> Boggs </PERSON> said. `` They did n't discover the error until early Monday,'' the lieutenant said, `` but they estimate that there were about 4,100 gallons of kerosene in the tank. `` That would make the mix about three-to-one,'' <PERSON> Boggs </PERSON> said. `` The owner estimates they sold from 730 to 800 gallons of the kerosene before learning that there was gasoline in it.'' By late Monday night, consumers had returned at least 200 gallons to the station, and only one minor fire had been linked to the mixture, officials said.
