<HEAD>Administration Opts Against Limitation on Bearing Imports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The domestic bearing industry is operating at or near 100 percent capacity, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration said in declining to limit imports of the friction-reducing components from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. The decision, announced Monday, follows a joint study by the Commerce and <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> departments. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> had found separately in July that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bearing manufacturers would not be able to meet `` all national security requirements in the event of a major conventional war.'' But President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in August tentatively ruled out limits until the joint study could be completed. The administration wanted to ensure that the domestic bearing industry would be sufficiently healthy to meet production needs in the event of an emergency, without the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> having to rely on outside suppliers. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the joint study found that conditions in the domestic bearing industry had improved signficantly in the last several months. His statement said that it was concluded that `` administration initiatives should be adequate to bring the domestic industrial base into an acceptable posture for national security purposes.'' Commerce Secretary <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Verity </PERSON> said in a statement that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s decision was made `` after a thorough review of the impact of bearing imports on national security.'' `` While recognizing the critical importance of bearings to defense preparedness, other administration initiatives already under way _ coupled with significantly improved economic conditions for the industry _ make me confident that this is the right decision,'' he said. The decision against moving to curb imports of bearings was based on these conclusions of the government investigators: _ Current demand for bearings in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is at its highest level in recent years, particularly as bearing-consuming industries such as automobiles, aerospace and off-road equipment experience heavy sales increases _ The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bearing industry has benefited from substantial increases in domestic demand and is operating at or near 100 percent of capacity _ The industry has attracted `` significant investment'' from both domestic - and foreign-owned _ A change in <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> acquisition guidelines last August, which now require the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> to use only domestic industries for the purchase of bearings for defense-related equipment This could provide the domestic industry with an estimated $ 40 million to $ 50 million in additional revenue for domestic suppliers. In a separate and unrelated action, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said it was `` aggressively pursuing'' an investigation of alleged unfair trade practices by foreign suppliers of anti-friction bearings. `` Our preliminary findings indicate dumping margins in the 20 to 80 percent range,'' <ORGANIZATION> Verity </ORGANIZATION> said. `` If the final results of this investigation verify these margins, the duties imposed could contribute to leveling the playing field for this important industry.'' He said that a final determination on the issue of dumping of bearings by foreign competitors in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market will be due Jan. 9, and a decision will be made 45 days later on what kind of actions to take. Dumping is the selling of a product in a foreign market at a price lower than the domestic price.
