<HEAD>Veteran Public Affairs Official Remains On White House Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, signed on for another hitch as <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, says President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` will have new ways of dealing with the press'' that may include more informal meetings with reporters. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, 46, has been President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s chief spokesman since February 1987 and was Vice President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s press secretary for two years before that. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, making his first appearance in the White House press briefing room since his election Nov. 8, announced Monday that he is retaining <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>. It is the first time the press secretary of an outgoing president has been named permanently to the job in a new administration, although <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinger </PERSON> served President <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> for an interim after President <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s assassination. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> declined to say how frequently <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would hold presidential news conferences, saying: `` The vice president has been holding press conferences at the rate of one every five hours for the last few weeks, so we'll have to see how that works out. `` The new president, I'm sure, will have new ways of dealing with the press. I'm sure there will be all kinds of interviews and press conferences and meetings.'' When a reporter observed that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> seems more comfortable than <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in freewheeling give-and-take with reporters, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said, `` I would agree with you that the president-elect is comfortable with the press, he does operate informally quite effectively.'' `` So I would suspect you might see a lot more informal _,'' the spokesman said, at which point his response was cut off by a reporter's question as to what he would recommend in the way of news conferences. `` I wo n't talk about all the things I've recommended and not recommended, but we'll just have to wait and see,'' he said. `` I think there should be as much contact with the press as possible and it should be as regular as possible,'' the spokesman said. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> is a veteran public affairs official whose federal career began in 1972 when he was a speechwriter for Secretary of Transportation <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Volpe </PERSON>. Before that, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> had worked for newspapers in his native <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>. `` I think he's the best,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` He represents the old and the new. He represents the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration and he also represents the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. ... This is continuity in the best sense.'' When asked if he would hold more frequent news conferences than <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, the president-elect said, `` I ` m going to lean heavily on <LOCATION> Marlin </LOCATION> for advice on this.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>'s present title is assistant to the president for press relations. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said that in the new administration <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> will be press secretary, a title held now by <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, who was wounded in the 1981 assassination attempt on President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. When asked whether <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> would have a role in the new administration, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said, `` I know the vice president is very interested in <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> and concerned about his well-being'' and that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his advisers `` have some ideas of things they would like him to do.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> would remain <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s press secretary through the transition, and he would take over on Jan. 20. Ms. <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> has said she plans to leave government. After <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> left the briefing room, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> opened his presentation with a few words of gratitude to the president-elect and president. Then a reporter asked him, `` Well, will you keep avoiding briefings and will you promise to hold more news conferences?'' `` A two-minute honeymoon,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` Amazing.''
