<HEAD>US-Soviet Grain Agreement Extended for 27 Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration hailed the new U.S.-Soviet grain agreement as providing a steady market for American farm products, but a congressman from <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s wheat belt said the deal sold growers short. The plan `` stabilizes grain trade between our two countries by ensuring a secure source of supply for Soviet grain imports and secure market for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grain exports,'' said a statement from <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmer </PERSON>, chief of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegation to the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> meetings. Under a 27-month extension of the long-term agreement between the two nations, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is promising to buy at the equivalent of at least 9 million metric tons annually of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grain. A metric ton equals about 2,205 pounds. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet negotiators signed the extension in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on Monday, breathing new life into a five-year plan that helped to turn the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> into one of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farmer's best customers. That agreement had expired Sept. 30. `` The extension will continue to stabilize grain trade between the two countries, benefiting American farmers,'' Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said in a statement. The agreement calls for the Soviets to buy at least 4 million metric tons each of wheat and corn annually as well as 1 million metric tons of additional wheat, corn, soybeans and soybean meal, or any combination of those commodities. The Soviets also are allowed to purchase up to 3 million metric tons of additional wheat and corn annually without further discussions. Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Glickman </PERSON>, D-Kan., and chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s subcommittee on wheat, soybeans and feed grains, said the pact has `` done nothing more than maintain the current agreement. `` This was an historic opportunity with one of our most important grain clients and all we can say is we did n't lose any ground,'' he said. `` That simply is n't good enough.'' `` This administration has driven down the price of grain in order to export more, but they do n't seem to be able to close the deal,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the Soviets bought 9.05 million tons of wheat, 5.18 million tons of corn, 830,700 tons of soybeans and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal for delivery in the fifth and final year of the current agreement. The Soviets purchased <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat for the final year and a half of the old agreement at federally subsidized prices under the government's Export Enhancement Program, designed to offset competition from the European Community and other suppliers. Under the 1985 program, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> pays private exporters in kind out of stocks held by the government-owned <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to ship the grain at highly attractive prices. There are no dollar estimates for these sales. A provision of the old plan carried over into the new version allows the Soviets to count one ton of soybeans or soybean meal as two tons and thus round out their purchase obligation by buying 500,000 tons of those commodities rather than a million tons of wheat or corn. `` In general our impression is favorable,'' <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Fields </PERSON> said. `` It's a continuation of what we had before, which worked fairly well.'' <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wheat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Growers </ORGANIZATION>, said his members were pleased with the agreement but had hoped that the amounts would have been a bit larger. In any case, he said, the plan was likely to have less effect on prices than will lingering problems caused by the drought. He said markets mainly would be relieved to get some assurance of continued Soviet demand. `` It's like a security blanket for some people,'' <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
