<HEAD>Candidates for Leadership of U.S. Senate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Following are profiles of the three candidates in today's
election of the next Senate majority leader:
^With PM-Senate Leader Bjt</NOTE>
<HEAD>GEORGE M. MITCHELL: Made His Name in Iran-Contra Hearings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> joined the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> eight years ago as an appointee who had never won election to public office. But the <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> Democrat has since proven himself a popular vote-getter, a thoughtful lawmaker and a telegenic party spokesman. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, a former federal judge, won praise for his incisive questioning of witnesses before the Iran-Contra investigating panel last year. He also hushed the hearing room with a statement as dramatic as the emotional testimony of Lt. Col. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>. `` Although he's regularly asked to do so, God does not take sides in <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> politics,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> lectured the Marine. `` And in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, disagreement with the policies of the government is not evidence of lack of patriotism.'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>'s Iran-Contra performance solidified his status as a potential majority leader. He was first mentioned for the job in 1986 when, as the hard-working head of the Democrats' senatorial campaign committee, he led his party back to control of the chamber. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, 55, had less legislative experience than his two opponents for <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> majority leader and was perceived as more liberal. As chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s environmental protection subcommittee, <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> led a losing fight this year for an anti-pollution bill designed to reduce acid rain, smog and airborne toxic chemicals. His powerful opponents included the current <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> majority leader, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, and Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> also chairs the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s health panel and has proposed a major long-term health care initiative. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> was appointed to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in 1980 to succeed <PERSON> Edmund </PERSON> <PERSON> Muskie </PERSON>, whom he had served as an executive assistant two decades earlier. He won election in 1982 with 61 percent of the vote and garnered 81 percent this year. The son of a utility company laborer and a Lebanese immigrant mother who worked the midnight shift at a woolen mill for 27 years, <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> graduated from <ORGANIZATION> Bowdoin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, spent two years as an <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> intelligence officer and worked as an insurance claims adjuster while attending night classes at <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> law school. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> lost a 1974 bid to become governor of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. He was appointed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney for the state in 1977 and two years later was named to a new federal judgeship in <LOCATION> Bangor </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>By Jill Lawrence</HEAD>
<HEAD>DANIEL K. INOUYE: A Deep-Voiced Presence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, the most senior of three candidates for <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> majority leader, is known for his solemn, deep-voiced presence which commands attention whether during a floor debate or at a hearing. <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON>, who has been a senator since 1962, earned national prominence first as keynote speaker at the Democratic National Convention in 1968, then gained added respect as a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Watergate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> committee </ORGANIZATION> in 1973. But the gloss was dulled somewhat last year when <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON> was criticized for not keeping a firm enough handle on hearings before the Iran-Contra investigating panel he helped chair. In that post and as former <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> chairman and a senior member of the <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON> has prided himself on being able to work closely with Republicans. But he also has been a party loyalist, backing President <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s Vietnam War policy and defending Sen. <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, in 1981 against expulsion in the Abscam case. His colleagues made him secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, the No. 3 party leadership position, leading many to rank him a year ago as the top prospect to succeed <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> as majority leader. But in recent months, <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON>'s chances seemed to fade as some _ particularly newer senators _ searched for a less ponderous figure to represent their numbers on television. Last year, <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON> was embarrassed after it was revealed that he had slipped into a money bill $ 8 million for a school in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> for North African Jews. He later was forced to rescind the provision. In recent years, his voting record has tended toward the liberal side: he has favored gun control, sanctions against <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and limits on political action committee contributions to candidates. He has opposed the Star Wars defense system and aid to the Nicaraguan Contras.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>By Jim Drinkard</HEAD>
<HEAD>J. BENNETT JOHNSTON: Cagey in the Senate's Back Rooms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> is an accomplished power broker with a reputation of knowing how to swing legislative deals while protecting his own interests. The Louisianan is chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and of the energy and water development appropriations subcommittee, posts from which he watches out for his state and its energy industry. That was seen by some observers as a possible disadvantage in his race for majority leader, since the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> already is led by another oil and gas advocate, Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>. While known for an easygoing, quotable style, <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> is quick to master details of legislation, has a strong grasp of <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> procedure and is considered a cagey backroom deal-maker. <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> was more conservative than either of his two rivals for majority leader. During his second term, he was a leading opponent of court-ordered busing to desegregate schools. But he now casts himself as a centrist. He dramatically came out against President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s nomination of conservative <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> last year, supported a bill aimed at reducing pollution that causes global warming, and fought <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s efforts to finance the Star Wars missile defense system. In the majority leader's race, <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> sold himself as the candidate most likely to appeal to <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and thus as the best standard-bearer for the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. He picked up endorsements from two of the party's stars, Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. Now 56, <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> entered the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in 1973 after a nine-year career in the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> state legislature.
</TEXT>
