<HEAD>Puget Sound `Spreads'; Some Worry About Dilution Of Identity</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY9</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Puget </PERSON>, circa 1792, would be proud. The meager waterway bearing his name has grown to encompass much of western <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s inland sea lanes, but critics say the expansion dilutes the Sound's identity. Some would stretch the edge of Puget Sound even farther _ to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s door _ but a <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> guide and amateur historian says Puget Sound has gone far enough. <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Manning </PERSON>, author of guides to the trails of western <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, would put the cutoff point near the north end of the <LOCATION> Kitsap </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>, across from the southern tip of <LOCATION> Whidbey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. To make his point, he would draw the line at <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION> <LOCATION> No </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION>, 20 miles north of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. `` It dilutes the identity of Puget Sound to spread it over too much water, and it lessens the identity of the other waterways,'' <PERSON> Manning </PERSON> said. Capt. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartzman </PERSON>, chairman of the state <ORGANIZATION> Pilotage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and a 25-year veteran of the state ferry system, agreed with that assessment. Any chart clearly shows that cutoff mark is the place where Admiralty Inlet links the Strait of <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuca </PERSON> with Puget Sound, he said. However, the borders ordered by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geographic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Names </ORGANIZATION> do n't quite comply with that description. And those with commerce in mind have much more divergent views. `` We figure ourselves as being on the north end of Puget Sound,'' said <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, manager of the <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Anacortes </LOCATION>, 40 miles north of Point No Point. Puget Sound `` includes us,'' said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, executive vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Bellingham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>, 20 miles north of <LOCATION> Anacortes </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said being part of Puget Sound, even when one is not, helps promote the area to outsiders. `` It gives an association with the larger metropolitan area of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` For the most part, we promote this area as being part of the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>, but when people ask us where's that, we say in Puget Sound, north of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. That disregards such waters as <LOCATION> Rosario </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saratoga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Passage </LOCATION>, the Strait of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, and the bays of <LOCATION> Skagit </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bellingham </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Padilla </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Manning </PERSON>. Those who extend Puget Sound past certain borders to include `` everything wet except martinis and rain'' are wrong, he said. The real names will die as newcomers are fed the `` Puget Sound'' pablum, he said. `` They do n't have the right to make such a radical change,'' he said. Capt. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Vancouver </PERSON>, the British explorer, first used the name after he sailed into the region's inland waters in 1792. He named the southern waters of what is now Puget Sound after one of his ship captains, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Puget </PERSON>. The name applied only to meandering inlets south of what is now <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION>. The main channel north of the <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Narrows </LOCATION> to the Strait of <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuca </PERSON>, named by earlier <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> explorers, was named Admiralty Inlet. In 1869, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> changed the description of Puget Sound to a general `` all the waters connected with the Strait of <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuca </PERSON> within the territory of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.''
