<HEAD>Activist Urges Democracy, Political Freedom For China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Chinese activist said in an essay published today that foreign countries should invest in his country only on condition the Communist government makes progress in human rights. <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> <PERSON> Wanding </PERSON> also criticized <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> of depriving its citizens of `` basic rights of citizenship'' such as voting in meaningful elections. His comments appeared in the English-language <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>. The <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> paper said the essay broke a 10-year silence by the activist, who was jailed for four years after figuring prominently in the Democracy Movement of 1978-79. Dissidents were allowed at the time to air their views by pasting character posters on a small <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> wall known as `` Democracy Wall,'' but the government soon cracked down. <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> founded the <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> in 1978 and authored a 19-point Human Rights Declaration before he was taken into custody in March 1979, the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said. In the essay, translated from Chinese to English by the newspaper, <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> recalled the movement he helped spearhead: `` The Democracy Wall dared to expose the problem of life-long tenure in office, the fact that ` ownership by the people' is state ownership, the existence of unemployment and surplus labor, and many other economic truths'' about <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, he wrote. Since the <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has opened to the outside world and sought overseas investment in a bid for modernization. But <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> urged foreign countries not to place more money in <LOCATION> Chin