rpres. He said many Romanians were migrating to towns to work in factories, where they get higher salaries than in agriculture. `` That's why resolute measures are needed for preventing the depopulation of rural settlements, for organizing them on a modern basis and creating conditions likely to provide inhabitants with everything they need for a decent, civilized life,'' <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON>'s comments drew differing interpretations. `` It's clear that <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> is backing off from his original statements, not because of mounting international opposition but due to lack of money and materials,'' said a former high-ranking official in the Romanian party who spoke on condition of anonymity. According to a summary of the speech distributed by <PERSON> Agerpres </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> departed from recent practice by not once mentioning the controversial village scheme by name. Last spring, he said at least half of <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s 13,000 villages `` must disappear.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> is holding its three-day meeting to review <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s long-term economic plans until the year 2000. <PERSON> Agerpres </PERSON> did not say why the meeting, originally scheduled for September, was delayed for two months.
