 <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s slightly relaxed rules for dormitory guests do n't go far enough, said a student who helped organize vigorous protests of a ban on overnight visitors of the opposite sex. University President <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Silber </PERSON> on Monday announced he had accepted the recommendations of a task force that decided to allow some overnight guests. The task force of parents, students, faculty and school officials was commissioned after thousands of students demonstrated against the ban. <PERSON> Silber </PERSON> limited overnight guests of the opposite sex to family members. Visits between 11 p.m. and 1 a.m. would have to be approved in writing by all roommates 24 hours in advance. But students remain forbidden from being overnight hosts to unrelated members of the opposite sex, and <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Carleton </PERSON>, a spokesman for the 27,000-student private school, said the rules changes probably wo n't go into effect until next fall. The recommendations do n't make the rules palatable because they do n't substantially change the original decision, said <PERSON> Susheel </PERSON> <PERSON> Srikonda </PERSON>, who, along with another student, formed a group called Active, Concerned, Together -LRB- ACT -RRB- to fight the new policies. ACT wanted to take a different approach that would emphasize roommate approval and give the resident assistants who are in charge of dormitories a larger role, he said. `` They are not changed that much,'' said <PERSON> Srikonda </PERSON>, a 20-year-old computer science major. <PERSON> Carleton </PERSON> disagreed. `` The initial policy that was proposed was that there be no overnight guests,'' he said. `` The tone of it was to discourage overnight guests. This is saying that there certainly can be overnight guests. It describes the format in which that can occur.'' The ban, announced in September, drew wide attention, including