<HEAD>China Claims Artifact At Sotheby's Auction Was Stolen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Sotheby </PERSON>'s withdrew an ancient bronze vessel from a sale of Chinese artifacts scheduled for today after the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government said the item had been stolen in June from a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> museum. The item was withdrawn from the auction of `` Fine Chinese Ceramics and Works of Arts'' at least two weeks ago after <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION>'s received a description of the missing museum piece from a representative of the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government, said a <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION>'s spokesman, <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> He said <PERSON> Sotheby </PERSON>'s was holding the ritual vessel, called a dui, pending a resolution of the dispute between the owner and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. According to the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Interpol </ORGANIZATION> office notified its <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> counterpart Saturday of the theft, and <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> police met Monday with a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> official to ask <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s help in recovering the object The Chinese government report said <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> police identified the dui from a color photograph in a Sotheby's catalog, which did not identify the owner and said it was expected to sell for $ 60,000 to $ 80,000. The vessel was made during <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s Warring States Period, from 475 B.C. to 221 B.C., a period of conflict among rival princes before what is now northern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> was unified under the first emperor. Chinese police say the dui in the catalog is identical in shape, decoration and patina spots to one that was stolen June 4 from the Qu Yuan Museum in <LOCATION> Zigui </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> in central <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Hubei </LOCATION> province. The thieves remain at large. The dui was excavated in the county in 1983. An expert at <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s Palace Museum said craftsmen at the time the piece was made were unable to cast identical bronze pieces. Millions of dollars worth of artifacts are smuggled out of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> each year, most through <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. Some are stolen from museums, but most are discovered by peasants in their fields or by tomb robbers, and the sites are wrecked before archaeologists can study them. <PERSON> Weigman </PERSON> said an auction `` would actually be the worst possible place'' to dispose of a stolen object because the process _ which includes the publication of photographs and detailed descriptions of every item _ is so public. In April, <PERSON> Sotheby </PERSON>'s withdrew a bronze statue of a Roman god from auction after experts determined that the statue belonged to the <LOCATION> Musee </LOCATION> des Beaux Arts et d'Archeologie in <LOCATION> Besancon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. The statue, worth $ 5,000, had been stolen in 1914, and was being sold through the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> auction house by the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION>. The <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> museum acquired it in 1953 from a donor who apparently did not know it had been stolen. Two scholars who saw the statue in a Sotheby's catalog questioned its authenticity, speculating it might be a copy of the missing bronze. Experts determined that, in fact, it was the missing bronze.
