ral committee,'' he said. If Labor joins a broad-based government under <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION>, it would be similar to the Cabinet that has ruled since 1984 elections gave neither Labor nor <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> enough seats to form a government without the other. In the new government, however, <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> would likely be prime minister for the entire four-year term. Under the power-sharing agreement reached after the 1984 vote, <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> and <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> each held the top post for two year.
