<HEAD>Hirohito's Temperature, Other Vital Signs Soar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s temperature and other vital signs soared today, 72 days after he fell ill with abdominal bleeding, the Imperial Palace said. The emperor had a fever of 102 at dusk, well above his normal 95.9 and among the worst readings recorded since he first vomited large amounts of blood on Sept. 19. <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s breathing quickened and his pulse rose to 115 beats per minute from recent levels of below 100, palace spokesman <PERSON> Kenji </PERSON> <PERSON> Maeda </PERSON> said. Officials had no further comment on his condition except to say chief physician <PERSON> Akira </PERSON> <PERSON> Takagi </PERSON> stayed beyond his normal hours tonight at <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s chambers in Fukiage Palace. Earlier today, <PERSON> Maeda </PERSON> said it was difficult to tell whether the 87-year-old monarch was asleep or awake. News reports say he is losing consciousness and family members say he sleeps through their visits. Doctors have transfused 45.4 pints of blood into him to combat the bleeding and control his anemia. <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> has eaten almost nothing in 72 days. There has been no official confirmation of reports he had cancer. <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> ascended the Chrysanthemum Throne on Christmas Day 1926 and has reigned almost 62 years, longer than any of the world's living monarchs After <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s defeat in World War II he became a largely powerless symbol of the state.
