<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Orientation Day for the Senate's Class of '88</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some of the 10 men who will take their places as freshman <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> senators next year felt awed by a sense of history, but others simply wanted to find their way from here to there. Monday was orientation day for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> class of 1988. And while the five Democrats and five Republicans all talked of tackling the federal government's massive deficit, their immediate concerns were more mundane: staff and office space, telephones, security and legislative procedure. Committee assignments were a pressing matter. There was much talk of exactly how low their place will be in the pecking order of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s seniority system. `` Everybody's worrying about numbers _ whether they'll be number 95, 96, 97, 98 or whatever,'' said Sen.-elect <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON>, R-Mont. `` I said, ` Boys, you ca n't get any lower than 100!''' That's <PERSON> Burns </PERSON>' number. One hundred _ and dead last in seniority. Rep. <PERSON> Connie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Fla </LOCATION>., figured he would be about 94th in seniority when all was said and done `` What does that get you?'' he was asked. `` Not very much, to tell you the truth,'' he replied. There are other numbers involved. Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, an ardent amateur historian who keeps track of such things, says that since the first <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> convened in 1789 there have been precisely 1,782 <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> When the 10 newcomers are sworn in with the convening of the 101st <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in January, they will be numbered 1,783 to 1,792, depending how on the final determination of their seniority is made under the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s complicated rules and procedures for such things. But for now, some of the members of the class of'88 were fairly glowing, even as they paid attention to what several called the `` nuts and bolts'' details of <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> life. `` It's a special day, a red letter day, a very personal day that you'll never forget,'' said Sen.-elect <PERSON> Herb </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>, D-Wis. `` But it's also like going to college as a `` Think of it. Father and mother immigrants _ 65 years ago _ had nothing. And now their son is a <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> senator.'' The son has a little more than nothing. A multimillionaire who spent some $ 5 million on his election campaign, <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> is owner of the <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bucks </ORGANIZATION> basketball team. <PERSON> Burns </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> farm broadcaster who upset Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Melcher </PERSON>, D-Mont., was asked to name the biggest challenge he faces as a new senator `` The biggest challenge to me is getting from here to there without walking through all these cameras,'' he said, waving a hand toward the forest of television cameras sprouting from the floor of a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> corridor. The new Democratic senators quickly found themselves the center of attention from three <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> veterans _ Sens. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Hawaii </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-La </LOCATION>., and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION> All sought votes in their bids to succeed <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> as <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> majority leader. <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> said he would vote for <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> because `` he's a person I feel comfortable with.'' <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Lieberman </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> said he would make up his mind at the last minute, adding that because he did n't know any of the three candidates all that well, `` it comes down to a decision you make in your gut.'' Still, there was a sense of wonder at being in a position to make such a choice at all. `` I feel a sense of history,'' said <PERSON> Lieberman </PERSON>. `` It's not going to be an easy time to be a <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> senator,'' he said, citing budget deficits, taxes and environmental problems. Sen.-elect <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Robb </PERSON>, a Democratic former governor of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, was told that the most frustrated senators are former governors, shorn of the ability to make executive decisions on their own authority. `` Thou sayest it,'' said <PERSON> Robb </PERSON>, who had little to say on any other subject. Three members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> _ <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>, <PERSON> Trent </PERSON> <PERSON> Lott </PERSON>, R-Miss., and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Jeffords </PERSON>, R-Vt. _ are moving across the Capitol to the For <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>, being one of 100 senators is a lot better than being one of 435 members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> with its restrictive traffic-cop rules. `` You have a much greater opportunity in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to influence legislation on the floor,'' <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> said. But for <PERSON> Lott </PERSON>, becoming a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> was n't an automatic step up. He gave up his No. 2 position in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> leadership to run for the seat being vacated by Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Stennis </PERSON>, D-Miss., a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> veteran `` You look at the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and there certainly are a lot of differences,'' <PERSON> Lott </PERSON> grumbled. `` Like why it takes three months in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to move in 10 guys when in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> they move in 43 people in 30 days.'' One new senator-to-be, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state Republican <PERSON> Slade </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorton </PERSON>, was making his second debut as a freshman. He was defeated by Democrat <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> in 1986 but reinstated by the voters on Nov. 8. Sen. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON>, D-Ill., who has been in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> for eight years, was asked if he had any advice for the newcomers `` I'll tell them to pray a lot,'' he said, grinning.
