<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Cabinet minister with the power to close newspapers is demanding damage payments from a major paper because it published an article poking fun at him and a critical letter from a reader, the newspaper said today. Home Affairs Minister <PERSON> Stoffel </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s action against The Star follows similar demands last week directed at a black newspaper he has already closed once, and at the editor of an anti-apartheid newspaper now under suspension. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> has the power under the 29-month state of emergency to close newspapers without giving reasons. Three newspapers have been closed temporarily by him this year. State-of-emergency regulations restrict reporting about unrest, security force actions, treatment of detainees, some forms of protest, and a range of statements the government considers subversive. Enforcement of the regulations has not been comprehensive. The <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, through the state attorney, was demanding 100,000 rand -LRB- $ 41,800 -RRB- for defamation and impairment of his dignity. The newspaper said police are also investigating it for alleged violations of laws dealing with the police and prisons, because of a photograph and a guest editorial it published. On Friday, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> demanded damage payments from <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nation </ORGANIZATION>, a black newspaper published by the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bishops </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, for publishing excerpts of a speech by <PERSON> Anton </PERSON> <PERSON> Harber </PERSON>, co-editor of The Weekly Mail. In the speech, <PERSON> Harber </PERSON> criticized <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s three-month banning of his newspaper and referred to the Cabinet minister as narrow-minded. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> is threatenin