<HEAD>Rights Court: Britain Violated Human Rights of Four Suspects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> violated the human rights of four men held under anti-terrorism laws in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> ruled today. It said <PERSON> Terrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Brogan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dermot </PERSON> <PERSON> Coyle </PERSON>, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> McFadden </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Tracey </PERSON> are entitled to compensation because they were denied speedy judicial hearings after their arrests in late 1984. Through <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION> lawyer <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Napier </PERSON>, the men said they would seek substantial damages and return to the European court if there were no amicable settlement. The four were detained for up to six days and 16 hours and released without charge. The court upheld <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s right to arrest suspected terrorists without charging them with a specific offense. But it said detainees must be granted a prompt hearing before a judge. The men were arrested as part of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s campaign against the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> that seeks to end British rule in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> through a campaign of terrorist violence. Roman Catholic nationalists in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> welcomed the decision, but legislators said the court failed to understand <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s battle against the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION>. The British government said it was studying the decision and would respond in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> at an unspecified date. `` We have to consider the human rights of the victims and potential victims of terrorism as well as those suspected of terrorist involvement,'' said a statement from the Home Office, which is responsible for law and order. <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION>'s legal political wing <ORGANIZATION> Sinn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fein </ORGANIZATION>, said: `` Once again the British have been found guilty of abusing human rights in the North.'' <PERSON> Merlyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Rees </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> lawmaker and former <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> minister responsible for <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, criticized the ruling. But he said <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> will have to accept it `` because part of our problem is convincing the world that we are not a repressive colonial government in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, a legislator from the governing Conservative party, said the judgment shows `` no understanding of the terrorist threat to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and the government should reject it out of hand.'' Under <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s anti-terrorism law persons simply suspected of terrorist activities can be arrested. But the European court found none of the men `` was either brought ` promptly' before a judicial authority or released ` promptly' following his arrest. The court did not define promptness except to say the human rights convention allows `` only a limited degree of flexibility'' to extend the duration of detention. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s Prevention of Terrorism Act permits suspected terrorists to be detained for 48 hours, although the government can extend that for another five days. According to latest figures available at the <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> Office, 411 were arrested between January and March this year, of whom 121 were held beyond 48 hours. The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> is part of the 21-nation Council of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the oldest organization working toward more European integration. The court's rulings are not legally binding but rarely are ignored.
</TEXT>
