<HEAD>Man Who Shot Muggers Sentenced on Drug Charge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A `` good Samaritan'' who shot two muggers asked for leniency on a 1987 drug conviction, but a judge who imposed a stiff sentence said he did not want to send a message to the public that it is `` OK to go and kill people.'' <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Slavin </PERSON> sentenced <PERSON> Clovis </PERSON> <PERSON> Fearon </PERSON> to 1 -LCB- to 4 -LCB- years in prison, only slightly less than the maximum two - to six-year sentence he could have received `` If he's such a fine person, why did he have a Brazilian-made Saturday night special?'' <PERSON> Slavin </PERSON> said at the sentencing Monday. `` You said you want to be an honest citizen; well, you can be an honest citizen when you get out of jail.'' <PERSON> Fearon </PERSON>, who came to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> five years ago, had pleaded guilty in February 1987 to felony charges for directing two undercover police officers to a drug dealer who sold them two vials of crack. A fugitive since March 1987 who had been living under an assumed name, <PERSON> Fearon </PERSON>'s identity was revealed Nov. 2 when he came to the rescue of a woman being robbed on the street outside his home. He killed one man and wounded another, using an unregistered handgun. `` I knew that getting involved could lead to my exposure,'' <PERSON> Fearon </PERSON> said at his sentencing. `` I did not want to get involved, but I knew I had to do something to help.'' <PERSON> Slavin </PERSON> last year had promised <PERSON> Fearon </PERSON> a sentence of one day in jail and five years probation on the drug conviction, but had warned him if he did not appear for sentencing he would impose a two - to six-year prison term <PERSON> Fearon </PERSON>, who read from a written statement, told the judge Monday that the reason he did not come to his sentencing was that an immigration lawyer had told him that he could be deported to <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>. `` I was afraid. I did not want to go back to <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> because I love <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. I know it is the land of opportunity,'' <PERSON> Fearon </PERSON> said. He said that after he became a fugitive he made a vow to himself to be a law-abiding citizen and had worked as many as three jobs at a time to support a wife and two children in <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Slavin </PERSON> said he reduced the sentence `` for his _ quote _ ` heroism.''' But the judge chided <PERSON> Fearon </PERSON> for going underground and changing his name and for owning the unlicensed gun which he used to shoot the two muggers. <PERSON> Fearon </PERSON> must serve the minimum of 1 -LCB- years before being eligible for parole. The mugging victim, <PERSON> Gertrude </PERSON> <PERSON> George </PERSON>, was not in court on Monday but had sent <PERSON> Slavin </PERSON> a letter urging him to be lenient. He had also received 50 other letters of support and petitions signed by people who lived in <PERSON> Fearon </PERSON>'s neighborhood of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Flatbush </LOCATION>.
