<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Lawyer     11-29 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Lawyer,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Says Ohio Court Erroneously Upheld Conviction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled today that an <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> court erroneously upheld the rape, robbery and assault convictions of a man whose court-appointed lawyer withdrew from the case. In an 8-1 decision, the high court said the <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> should not have decided on <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Penson </PERSON>'s appeal of rape, robbery and assault convictions without first appointing a new attorney to handle the case. `` The need for forceful advocacy does not come to an abrupt halt as the legal proceeding moves from the trial to appellate stage,'' Justice <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> wrote for the court, which ordered further hearings on the case. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> tribunal `` erred by failing to appoint new counsel to represent petitioner'' after determining that <PERSON> Penson </PERSON>'s case raised several possible legal issues for appellate review <PERSON> Penson </PERSON>'s original court-appointed lawyer was allowed to withdraw from the appeal after filing a statement that he found no legal errors by the trial judge that required reversal of the convictions. The appeals court then denied <PERSON> Penson </PERSON>'s request for a new lawyer but later reviewed the trial record and found that the defendant had `` several arguable claims.'' The court reversed one of the three convictions stemming from <PERSON> Penson </PERSON>'s involvement with two other men in the Aug. 4, 1984, break-in of a <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, home. But it ultimately concluded that <PERSON> Penson </PERSON> `` suffered no prejudice'' from his court-appointed lawyer's `` failure to give a more conscientious examination of the record'' and upheld the remaining two convictions. <PERSON> Penson </PERSON>, who is serving an 18-to-28-year sentence, was one of three men convicted of breaking into the home and sexually assaulting a man and two women, who were also robbed. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> court violated standards set by the high court in a 1967 opinion for judging the effectiveness of court-appointed lawyers handling appeals. `` Both stages of the prosecution, although perhaps involving unique legal skills, require careful advocacy to ensure that rights are not foregone and that substantial legal and factual arguments are not inadvertently passed over,'' <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> wrote in an opinion that drew a dissent from Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON>. `` It bears emphasis that the right to be represented by counsel is among the most fundamental rights,'' <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> wrote. `` We have long recognized that ` lawyers in criminal courts are necessities, not luxuries','' the court's majority said, quoting from its landmark 1963 decision in <PERSON> Gideon </PERSON> v. <PERSON> Wainwright </PERSON> that mandated court-appointed lawyers for indigent defendants. But <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> called the decision `` a futile monument to the court's effort to guarantee to the indigent appellant what no court can guarantee him: exactly the same sort of legal services that would be provided suitably by retained private counsel.'' <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> court's review of the trial record without assistance of <PERSON> Penson </PERSON>'s lawyer resulted in the proper finding that the defendant's rights were not prejudiced. But the court's majority rejected this view, saying that the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> tribunal could not justify its refusal to appoint a new lawyer on the ground there was no merit to <PERSON> Penson </PERSON>'s appeal. `` Finding harmless error or a lack of ... prejudice in cases such as this, however, would leave criminal appealants without any protections'' under the 1967 decision, <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> wrote. The case is <PERSON> Penson </PERSON> v. <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, 87-6116.
</TEXT>
