<HEAD>Witness: Steinberg Slapped Child for No Asparent Reason</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man on trial for murder in the beating of his illegally adopted daughter once whacked the sleeping 6-year-old in the face `` out of the clear blue sky,'' a witness testified. The witness, alleged drug dealer <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Scannapieco </PERSON>, on Monday became the first person to testify that he actually saw <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, a now-disbarred lawyer, strike <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>. <PERSON> Scannapieco </PERSON> said <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> hit the girl hard enough `` to bring tears'' and for no apparent reason. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> faces a $ 3 million lawsuit filed by his former live-in lover, <PERSON> Hedda </PERSON> <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON>. The suit, filed in state court Monday, alleges <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> assaulted and tortured her for most of the 11 years they lived together. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> also charged that he used humiliation, brainwashing, drugs and the withholding of food to teach her that `` she was a worthless person who could only be saved through his wisdom and special powers.'' <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> is expected to testify against <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> in the murder trial. <PERSON> Scannapieco </PERSON>, who has been indicted on narcotics charges, had hired <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> to represent him. <PERSON> Scannapieco </PERSON> said he saw <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> strike <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> on Oct. 23, 1987, as <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> drove them to <PERSON> Scannapieco </PERSON>'s home in <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Katrine </LOCATION> in upstate <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. More than 20 witnesses have testified against <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> so far, but <PERSON> Scannapieco </PERSON> is the first to report having seen <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> strike the girl. `` Right after she fell asleep,'' <PERSON> Scannapieco </PERSON> said, `` right out of the clear blue sky, Mr. <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> took his hand and went ... -LRB- demonstrating the blow -RRB- SMASH!'' <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothwax </PERSON> struck the word `` smash'' from the record at the request of <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s lawyer, <LOCATION> Ira </LOCATION> <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. Demonstrating the blow, <PERSON> Scannapieco </PERSON> slammed the back of his hand against the judge's bench. The judge, <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> and the jurors seemed startled. <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> smiled and shook his head as if in disbelief at Scannapieco's dramatic gesture. <PERSON> Scannapieco </PERSON> said the slap on the right side of <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>'s face `` was pretty forceful, enough to bring tears to your eyes.'' She woke up and looked at <LOCATION> Steinberg </LOCATION>, who told her to `` stop staring at him and keep blinking and smiling. Keep blinking and smiling _ that's what she was told to do,'' <PERSON> Scannapieco </PERSON> said. He said <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> told <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> this five or six times. <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> did not seem angry, <PERSON> Scannapieco </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Scannapieco </PERSON> said <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> told him he hit the child because she sometimes slowed her heart and breathing, putting herself into a near coma. He quoted <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> as saying it was a medical condition that `` got so serious one time that he had to put her in the hospital.'' <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> was removed unconscious from <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION> apartment on Nov. 2, 1987, and died of head injuries three days later. <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> has denied hitting the child. He has said she fell unconscious after choking on food and that he caused bruises on her chest and back while trying to revive her. A report in Monday's <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newsday </ORGANIZATION> quoted court sources as saying that in the month before <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>'s death, <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> free-based cocaine nightly from a kilogram that had been left with him for safekeeping by a client.
