<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The husband of a woman accused of snatching an infant from a hospital nursery thought his wife had just given birth and was unaware that she had faked her pregnancy, police and prosecutors say. <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Newkirk </PERSON>, 36, was arraigned Monday on kidnapping charges in the abduction of 2 -LCB- - month-old <PERSON> Debra </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, who was taken from a crib at C.S <PERSON> Mott </PERSON> <PERSON> Children </PERSON>'s Hospital on Friday. <PERSON> Bond </PERSON> was set at $ 300,000 and a hearing was set for Dec. 7. But authorities dropped charges against her husband, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON>. `` We're fairly well convinced he did not know his wife planned to kidnap the baby,'' said Police Lt. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Atkinson </PERSON>. He said <PERSON> Newkirk </PERSON> was released after he passed a polygraph test Monday. `` -LRB- <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Newkirk </PERSON> -RRB- was telling him she was pregnant all along, that she has small babies and that she has them quick,'' <PERSON> Atkinson </PERSON> said. `` She really built this up in his mind.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Newkirk </PERSON> allegedly made medical appointments at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> and told her husband she was visiting an obstetrician, <PERSON> Atkinson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Newkirk </PERSON> said he would stand by his wife. `` I do n't think she knew what she was doing,'' he said. `` I thought it was my child.'' The Newkirks, of <PERSON> Howell </PERSON>, were arrested Saturday when they pulled into the driveway of their home in <PERSON> Howell </PERSON>. Police said they found the baby in their car. Witnesses said the Newkirks showed off the child at <PERSON> Cleary </PERSON>'s Pub in <PERSON> Howell </PERSON> about an hour after the 4 -LCB- - pound child was reported missing <PERSON> Debra </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> was receiving medication at the hospital for breathing problems when she was taken. The premature infant also was hooked up to electronic monitoring equipment and required feeding every three hours to prevent dehydration. Her twin brother was left undisturbed in his nearby crib. The baby's 17-year-old mother, <PERSON> Kimberly </PERSON> <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> of <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON>, was n't at the hospital when her child was taken. The infant was returned to C.S. <PERSON> Mott </PERSON> on Saturday, and was listed in good condition Monday.
