<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pardon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> today withdrew its recommendation of leniency for a man who killed a man nearly 20 years ago and later escaped from prison to build a new life in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>. The withdrawal came three weeks after <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Staggs </PERSON> was arrested in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> on sexual abuse charges based on allegations made by a stepdaughter and a niece. During 17 years as a fugitive from <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Staggs </PERSON> raised a family and operated an auto repair shop in <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> finally tracked him down last February, and he was returned to <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>. After a pardon board hearing in which <PERSON> Staggs </PERSON>' attorney presented petitions signed by 2,000 <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> residents asking for leniency, the five members recommended a six-month sentence. Gov. <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> refused to accept the recommendation, asking the board to reconsider. Before the pardon board could reconsider, <PERSON> Staggs </PERSON> was arrested in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>. `` Based on the current situation in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, the indictments being of such serious nature, the board recommended that any form of leniency be withdrawn,'' <PERSON> Annette </PERSON> <PERSON> Viator </PERSON>, attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corrections </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, said today. `` If he's found innocent, then he could apply here again for leniency. By law, he can do that within a year of being denied,'' she said. Shortly after <PERSON> Staggs </PERSON>' arrest in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> on the sexual abuse charges, the niece recanted her testimony, saying <PERSON> Staggs </PERSON> had only touched her breast and that may have been accidental. A grand jury received the case on Nov. 16 and is to decide whether to indict <PERSON> Staggs </PERSON> on three counts of aggravated sexual battery and one count of aggravated rape. At a Nov. 16 hearing, <PERSON> Staggs </PERSON>' 10-year-old stepdaughter testified about several alleged sexual encounters with <PERSON> Staggs </PERSON>. Prosecutors also presented a tape-recording of a 90-minute meeting Sept. 30 between <PERSON> Staggs </PERSON> and his sister, <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON>, who was equipped with a hidden microphone by the <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigation </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Staggs </PERSON> allegedly told Mrs. <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON> that some of the allegations his stepdaughter made were accurate. `` She did it on her own free will,'' <PERSON> Staggs </PERSON> said on tape. `` Tell her that whatever happened in the past, I'm sorry for. Tell her I do n't blame her. I do n't hold it against her. I need psychiatric help.'' <PERSON> Staggs </PERSON> was being held in the <LOCATION> Maury </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, Jail in lieu of $ 250,000 bond.
