<HEAD>NRC Orders Inspections For Counterfeit Parts At Nuclear Plants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday it has ordered operators of all commercial nuclear power plants to check their safety systems for counterfeit and possibly faulty circuit breakers. Spokesman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Ingram </PERSON> said the order, issued Nov. 22 to the 110 plants, noted that recent inspections `` indicate a potential safety concern.'' But he said there have been no instances where a counterfeit or faulty breaker was blamed for an accident of any kind at a nuclear plant. The order for inspections, which must be carried out by March 1, followed an <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> investigation into allegations that four <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> firms had sold counterfeit breakers to nuclear plants. <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> reported in July that it had found 30 counterfeit breakers in its inventory at the <LOCATION> Diablo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canyon </LOCATION> nuclear plant near <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Luis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Obispo </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> found in the same month that it had bought 16 potentially counterfeit breakers for its <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Onofre </LOCATION> plant, 55 miles south of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> said in the bulletin that the inspections are necessary `` to provide reasonable assurance that nuclear power plants can be operated without undue risk to the public health and safety.'' The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> has found `` numerous failures'' of certain types of circuit breakers during preliminary commission-supervised tests, the bulletin said. If a potentially counterfeit breaker is found already installed _ and it can not be immediately tested _ the utility must submit `` an analysis justifying continued operation,'' the bulletin said. The <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported that the inspection plan was criticized in a memorandum attached to the bulletin by <ORGANIZATION> Underwriters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION>, a nonprofit testing agency that certifies circuit breakers. `` The test program is not adequate to provide assurance that the tested ... circuit breakers would be suitable for their intended purpose,'' the laboratory said. The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> responded by saying that it `` considers the test program to provide a reasonable assurance of performance requirements and characteristics most important to ensuring reactor safety.'' The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> has told utilities that more than 50 companies may be counterfeiting circuit breakers and other electrical components.
