<HEAD>Government Gets Tough, Calling in Army to Ease Transport Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soldiers in army trucks rolled into the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> region Tuesday to help transport hundreds of thousands of suburban commuters stranded by a transit strike the government called `` union guerrilla warfare.'' The strike called by the communist-led <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Confederation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> paralyzed two of four lines on the regional express network and was spreading to city subway and bus services. On Monday night, the French government ordered more than 350 military trucks and 1,000 soldiers to supplement private companies called in to move passengers. The military contingent, from Dijon and other areas, was expected to be in operation for morning rush hour Wednesday, with 250 trucks at the suburban terminals of the affected lines, according to Prefect <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON> <PERSON> Philip </PERSON>, governor of the <LOCATION> Ile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> region. It was expected to take up to 48 hours for all 365 military vehicles to be operational. `` Deterioration of public services forces the government to assume its responsibilities,'' President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> said. `` That is what the government has done, and done well, notably in calling in the army.'' The transit strike is one of a string of work stoppages plaguing <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> for more than a month. Public sector employees ranging from postal workers to nurses, ambulance drivers and even funeral parlor employees have been striking sporadically for increased wages and other benefits. Socialist Premier <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON>, in power for six months, has remained firm in the face of demands, continuing the tight spending policies in force since 1983. Transport Minister <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Delebarre </PERSON> ordered strikers' wages suspended and punishment of those engaged in what he said were illegal acts. He said some strikers blocked buses in their terminals, flattened tires and sabotaged engines. This amounted to `` a sort of union guerrilla warfare of harassment'' in which `` hundreds of thousands of users were being taken hostage,'' the minister said. Blocked terminals, maintenance depots and lack of material were forcing a reduction in city bus and <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION> service, with buses running at about 60 percent capacity at rush hour Tuesday and one <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION> line shut down. The transit authority decided over the weekend to close down the two suburban train lines starting Monday, saying safety could no longer be assured because of the strikers, whose strength is concentrated in the train maintenance forces. <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Krasucki </PERSON>, secretary-general of the labor federation, denounced what he called government tactics of `` repression, sanctions and intimidation'' which he said will only `` increase the fighting spirit'' of the strikers. Workers, with an average monthly salary of about $ 1,100, are demanding a $ 170 monthly increase plus improved safety measures. The transit authority most recently proposed increases of about $ 25 plus bonuses ranging from about $ 17 to $ 100. Opposition politicians have criticized <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON>, saying he has failed to define a policy to deal with public sector grievances. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, re-elected to a seven-year term in May, had made social peace a main campaign pledge. The strike action fanned by the labor federation is widely regarded as a <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> effort to undermine the government and strengthen its own hand for municipal elections in March. Party officials deny they are using social discontent for political benefit, and <PERSON> Krasucki </PERSON> said the idea was `` completely stupid.'' Job grievances have affected many sectors this fall. Striking postal workers left <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> without mail service for three weeks earlier this month, and mail strikes continue in <LOCATION> Lyon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Amiens </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Clermont-Ferrand </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Marseille </ORGANIZATION> has been hit with strikes by train and bus drivers and social security workers, who are refusing to work in several provincial cities. Other job actions are being carried out at nuclear plants, in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> pharmacies and at the <LOCATION> Louvre </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Museum </LOCATION>, where guards protesting a change in work hours have been off the job for more than a week.
