<HEAD>Pentagon Chief Making Final Visit to Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> next week will visit four <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> states that have provided limited support for American forces in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials say. A stop aboard <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships in the gulf also is on the itinerary for what was expected to be <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>'s last tour before the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration leaves office in January, said the officials, who asked not to be identified. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> would discuss a variety of regional issues with officials in <LOCATION> Oman </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>. These presumably would include the scaling back of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces following the Iraq-Iran cease-fire. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> is including the gulf on a 10-day trip that begins with defense meetings in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> and at NATO headquarters in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>. Gulf-based sources, insisting on anonymity, said <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>'s visit was primarily in response to an invitation from <LOCATION> Oman </LOCATION>'s defense minister, <PERSON> Mutassim </PERSON> <PERSON> Bin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamoud </PERSON> <PERSON> Busaidi </PERSON>. The other stops were added for diplomatic reasons, they said. All four <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> states, though nominally neutral in the Iraq-Iran war, have made facilities of one kind or another available to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces since mid-1987, when the escalating conflict prompted a major buildup of American and other foreign naval units in the gulf. Despite the Aug. 20 cease-fire, in effect ending eight years of Iraq-Iran hostilities, 11 Kuwait-owned oil tankers reflagged by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> last year for protection still sail under the Stars and Stripes. The sources said <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>'s acceptance of the Omani invitation reflected <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest in nurturing a relationship that gained strength during the war, yet remains more secretive than <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ties with any other gulf Arab state. The Omanis permit <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships to refuel at a naval depot on the Arabian Sea. They have served three times in the past 15 months as diplomatic go-betweens for the repatriation of Iranians captured or rescued at sea by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces. The Omanis, who share control of the <ORGANIZATION> Strait </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hormuz </ORGANIZATION>, the strategic gateway to the gulf, with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, have longstanding military ties with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. However, they also are the only gulf state to participate in annual `` Bright Star'' military maneuvers with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials say the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will reduce its fleet if the Iraq-Iran truce continues to hold, but have given no timetable. Already trimmed by two ships from 27 to 25, it remains the largest of six foreign navies in the region. The gulf-based squadron of 15 returned to full strength Sunday when the amphibious assault ship USS Raleigh arrived after a month's delay for repairs It carries a 400-man <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> combat force. European navies are withdrawing more rapidly, with <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>'s last minesweeper recently departed, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>' last leaving Dec. 2 and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s five warships heading home before Dec. 31.
