<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A computer failure that cost the state up to $ 700,000 in lost lottery ticket sales is being investigated by specialists from the firm that set up the troubled `` Lotto 6-49'' terminals, officials said. Experts from <ORGANIZATION> GTECH </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Providence </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION>, were to inspect the software that caused the 3-year-old lottery's worst computer breakdown. The computer crash came as the state was ending an investigation of problems with <ORGANIZATION> GTECH </ORGANIZATION>, which has been fined $ 1.7 million for computer mishaps since the company got the `` Lotto 6-49'' contract in October 1986. A report of the investigation is due Friday, said lottery director <PERSON> Chon </PERSON> <PERSON> Gutierrez </PERSON>. The computer failure Saturday night affected up to 4,700 of the state lottery's 7,200 `` Lotto 6-49'' terminals. A backup system restored service to all but 120 terminals about 12 minutes later, lottery spokeswoman <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kossack </PERSON> said. `` What is unusual is that all of the terminals on the backup system did not come back up,'' she said. In spite of the outage, three players picked all six numbers correctly to win $ 2 million each. <ORGANIZATION> GTECH </ORGANIZATION>, which operates Lotto under a $ 220 million five-year contract with the state, is subject to fines for each minute of computer lapse that occurs up to eight hours before the Wednesday and Saturday drawings. <ORGANIZATION> GTECH </ORGANIZATION> faces a fine of `` close to $ 200,000'' as a result of the failure, lottery computer director <PERSON> Joanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. However, <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrissey </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> GTECH </ORGANIZATION>'s senior vice president, told the <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION