<HEAD>FAA Wants Airlines to Modify Takeoff Alarms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> today proposed modifications in the takeoff alarm systems on virtually all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commercial jetliners to guard against electrical failures, officials said. The directive, which would apply to more than 3,700 commercial jets, would require installation of a warning light in the cockpit to warn pilots when the takeoff alarm system loses electrical power, the agency said. The alarm is designed to alert a pilot that his plane, and especially control devices such as wing flaps, is not in the proper configuration for a takeoff. Airlines have until February to comment on the proposal and then a year to comply, although some air carriers are expected to make the changes sooner, officials said. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials said the modifications are not expected to interrupt normal airline service because they likely will be done during routine maintenance and would probably take only about 20 hours of work per plane. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said installation of the cockpit light, which must be clearly visible to all flight crew members, is estimated to cost about $ 1,050 per aircraft. The crash on Aug. 16, 1987 of <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> Flight 255 during a takeoff from <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION> was blamed on the failure of the flight crew to set the plane's wing flaps properly for takeoff. The crashed killed 156 people. Investigators also are examining the possibility of an improper flap setting in the crash of a <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> jet at <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> last August in which 14 of the 108 people aboard were killed. There was no sounding of the takeoff alarm system in that aircraft either. The <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> crash involved a <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> MD-80, while the crash in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> involved a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727. According the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>, the directive will cover virtually all commercial jetliners including those produced by the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Airbus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrie </ORGANIZATION>, the European aircraft manufacturing consortium. In some aircraft, the modification may already have been made, one source said. The FAA-directed correction is aimed at warning the flight crew of an electrical short in the alarm system as some investigators have suggested likely occurred in the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> jetliner that crashed in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> last May concluded that <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> Flight 255 crashed because the pilots did not set the wing flaps to the proper takeoff position, preventing the MD-80 from gaining proper lift. The <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> determined in the investigation that the alarm, which governed the takeoff flaps, did not sound because of an interruption of electrical power. Investigators could not determine conclusively what caused the power interruption, the safety board said. At the time, however, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> maintained that there was a possible inherent problem with the alarm systems that made them susceptible to electrical problems. The <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> said it could not determine whether the electrical short was due to such a defect, but also did not rule out the possibility that the flight crew might have pulled a circuit breaker to prevent nuisance alarms.
