<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A graying group of civil rights warriors, some black and some Jewish, gathered to take a look back at their coalition against segregation and to acknowledge things are no longer the same between them. `` We are not bosom buddies in the way we were in the intense days of the'60s,'' said <PERSON> Courtland </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>, a black man from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> who was among about 70 participants in Monday's sessions of a conference aimed at chronicling black-Jewish cooperation. <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> and several other black speakers emphasized the potential for reuniting the groups, which have sometimes clashed over methods of integration, the rights of Palestinians under the Jewish government of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and alleged anti-Semitism by some blacks. `` There was some ambivalence where the movement was split, but now we can heal those splits,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Fredericksburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, a black who helped found the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Racial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equality </ORGANIZATION>. Farmer recalled his trip to <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> in 1964 to investigate the disappearances of three civil rights workers. Two of them, <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwerner </PERSON>, were Jewish, and <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> authorities referred to them as `` Jew boys.'' The two, along with a black man, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON>, were later found dead. Even earlier, <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON> said, Jews became natural allies of blacks because of anti-Semitism fanned by the <ORGANIZATION> Ku </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klan </ORGANIZATION> and the lynching of Jewish businessman <PERSON> Leo </PERSON