pabilities Shortly after retiring from the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, Tower was named a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arms control negotiator in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> where he concentrated on reduction of long-range nuclear weapons. He quit that post after 14 months for what <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said privately were family reasons and because he believed the job lacked excitement. In November 1986, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> chose Tower to head a commission investigating the Iran-Contra affair. In its final report issued in February 1987, the panel blamed the arms-for-hostages dealing in part on <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s laid-back management style. It had little to say about any possible <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> involvement. Tower gained national attention in 1960 when he lost to Democratic Sen. <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, who ran for both re-election and the vice presidency. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> resigned his <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seat and Tower defeated the appointed replacement, Democrat <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blakley </PERSON>, in a special election, by a mere 8,000-vote margin. The son of a Methodist minister, <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION>, a one-time Democrat, former radio announcer and insurance salesman, was the first Republican elected by <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> voters to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. Two <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> senators in the post-Civil War period had been named by the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>. In the earlier campaign against <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, the 5-foot-6 Tower won over voters with his self-deprecating line, `` My name is Tower _ but you can see that I do n't.'' In his last re-election campaign, <PERSON> Tower </PERSON> refused to shake his opponent's hand when they m