<HEAD>High Court Won't Fault Police For Evidence Loss</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A divided <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in a decision some members said is unnecessarily sweeping, ruled Tuesday the rights of criminal defendants are not violated when police unintentionally fail to preserve potentially vital evidence. The court also said the Constitution does not require police to conduct state-of-the-art tests in examining evidence. By a 6-3 vote, the justices reinstated an <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> man's conviction in the kidnaping and sodomizing of a 10-year-old boy The justices reversed a lower court ruling that the man's rights were violated because police failed to preserve and analyze properly semen samples from the child's body and clothing _ evidence which, in theory, could have exonerated the defendant. In another decision, the high court reinforced the right of the poor to have a lawyer's help in appealing convictions. The justices, voting 8-1, said an <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> appeals court improperly allowed an attorney to withdraw from representing a convicted rapist and robber without explaining in detail why he believed an appeal was frivolous. In the <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> case, an appeals court threw out the conviction and 10-year prison sentence of <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Youngblood </PERSON>. He was convicted of kidnapping a boy on Oct. 29, 1983 from a church carnival in the <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION> area. Police said the boy was driven to a house, raped four times during a 90-minute ordeal and then released. Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON>, in his opinion for the high court Tuesday, said <PERSON> Youngblood </PERSON> did not prove that police deliberately failed to preserve evidence. `` Unless a criminal defendant can show bad faith on the part of the police, failure to preserve potentially useful evidence does not constitute a denial of due process of law,'' <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> said. `` Requiring a defendant to show bad faith on the part of police both limits the extent of the police's obligation to preserve evidence to reasonable bounds and confines it to ... those cases in which police themselves ... indicate that the evidence could form a basis for exonerating the defendant,'' he said. <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> said the obligation of authorities to preserve evidence is not as great as their duty to turn over to defendants all existing evidence, including material that could help acquit the accused. Also, he continued, the Constitution does not require police to use the best available technology to test the reliability of evidence. Comparing the case to one in which police fail to use a Breathalyzer to determine if a motorist was intoxicated, he added, `` Police do not have a constitutional duty to perform any particular tests.'' But Justice <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON>, in a dissenting opinion, said police `` ineptitude'' deprived <PERSON> Youngblood </PERSON> of his right to a fair trial. `` The Constitution requires that criminal defendants be provided with a fair trial, not merely a good faith try at a fair trial,'' he said. `` By what may have been nothing more than police ineptitude, -LRB- <PERSON> Youngblood </PERSON> -RRB- was denied the opportunity to present a full defense.'' <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> also said there was no need for the court to decide whether police must use the cutting edge of technology in analyzing evidence. He was joined by Justices <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>. Justice <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> joined the majority in voting to reinstate <PERSON> Youngblood </PERSON>'s conviction. But <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said the court went too far in holding that criminal defendants must prove bad faith by police when crucial evidence is lost or destroyed. <PERSON> Youngblood </PERSON>, convicted of child molesting, sexual assault and kidnapping, was identified as the assailant from police photographs shown to the boy. Laboratory specialists found traces of semen on the boy and also in clothing he was wearing. It was not until a year later that the semen was tested to determine blood typing of the assailant. But no blood group substances were found. The semen sample taken from the boy's body was refrigerated. The clothing, which might have contained a larger quantity of semen, was not. <PERSON> Youngblood </PERSON> was determined to be what is known as a secretor, with blood type A. That means that his blood group could be determined from his semen. The absence of blood group substances in the semen taken from the victim suggested that the boy's attacker either was a non-secretor or that the samples were too small to determine blood type. There also was testimony that technologically advanced tests to determine blood grouping were not performed on the semen samples. An <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> appeals court threw out <PERSON> Youngblood </PERSON>'s conviction on grounds that had state-of-the-art tests been performed and had the best technology been used to preserve the evidence, <PERSON> Youngblood </PERSON> might have been found innocent.
</TEXT>
