rial numbers; and three counts of using false travel documents. <PERSON> Kunstler </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kuby </PERSON> said they would appeal <PERSON> Lechner </PERSON>'s refusal to find a state trooper's search of <PERSON> Kikumura </PERSON>'s car unconstitutional and thus suppress the evidence. They said they also will seek to trim the number of counts in the indictment and to dismiss the case because of the prison phone recordings. The arresting trooper said at an October hearing that the bombs were in plain view in <LOCATION> Kikumura </LOCATION>'s car and that <PERSON> Kikumura </PERSON> acted suspiciously. <PERSON> Kikumura </PERSON> said the bombs were in the trunk, that he was not acting suspiciously and that he never gave permission to search his car. <PERSON> Lechner </PERSON> said he found the trooper more credible. He did not mention the witness testimony of a gas station attendant who supported Kikumura's version. <PERSON> Kunstler </PERSON> said he never asked his client what he was doing in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
