<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Larkin </PERSON>, head of the 300,000-member Roman Catholic diocese of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Petersburg </LOCATION> since 1979, announced Tuesday he is retiring for health reasons. <PERSON> Larkin </PERSON>, 65, said his retirement had been accepted by Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>. Bishops must offer their resignation at age 75. `` When I began my tenure as bishop I fully intended to remain until the mandatory retirement age,'' said <PERSON> Larkin </PERSON>. `` However, although man proposes, God disposes. During the past year my health has not been the best and I was advised to slow down.'' He did not disclose the nature of his medical condition. For nine years, the <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Morris </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, native has been head of the growing five-county <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> diocese, which has 71 parishes and missions, more than 200 priests, nearly 400 religious sisters and brothers, 30 schools and 12,000 students. <PERSON> Larkin </PERSON>, who was ordained in <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, in 1947, was named bishop in 1979 following the death of <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON>. He will remain bishop until a successor is named by the pope.
