<HEAD>Rare Napoleon Letter, Books, Manuscripts Auctioned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A handwritten letter by <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonaparte </PERSON> outlining secret plans to invade <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> sold at auction Tuesday for $ 21,186 to a French collector. This rare glimpse of <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON>'s genius was the highlight of a sale of rare books letters and manuscripts of some of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s most famous writers. `` The four-page letter in <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON>'s own hand is a piece of French history,'' said <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Tajan </PERSON> of the Ader-Picard-Tajan auction house. `` If the plan to invade <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> had worked, the map of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> may well have been modified.'' The buyer's identity was not revealed. An unusually rare eight-volume edition of the works of Moliere _ creator of French high comedy _ was sold for $ 322,000 to the <ORGANIZATION> Bibliotheque </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationale </ORGANIZATION>. It is one of four first editions dating from 1673. The sale at the year-old Drouot auction house annex, off the Champs Elysees, attracted military history buffs and bibliophiles. It offered 50 pages of letters written by the French novelist <PERSON> Stendhal </PERSON> while he followed <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON>'s armies in 1812-13. In one letter, he describes the horror of the burning of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> while complaining about his empty stomach, nagging toothache and the vulgarity of his compatriots. One addressed to his sister, dated Oct. 4, 1812, went to the French Archives for $ 35,590. `` We left the city, illuminated by the most beautiful fire in the world ... The moon, I believe, shone above the fire. It was a great spectacle, but one had to be alone to see it. This is the sad condition which ruined for me the <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> campaign: to have been with people who would have destroyed the Colosseum and the sea of <LOCATION> Naples </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Stendhal </PERSON> wrote. All items were part of the vast collection of <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Guerin </PERSON>, leading French collector and the man who defended the young <PERSON> Marcel </PERSON> <PERSON> Proust </PERSON> long before `` Remembrance of Things Past'' was universally acclaimed. The letter from <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> to Admiral Ganteaume, written Dec. 7, 1803, details three daring strategies for maneuvering 60 French ships across the English Channel. `` Let us be masters of the strait for six hours and we will be masters of the world,'' <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> wrote. The most complex of the plans involved moving one fleet to <LOCATION> Toulon </LOCATION> and another toward <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION> to trick <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s Lord <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> into heading for <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, while British land forces would be tied up protecting the country's western coast against the fleet headed for <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>. None of the plans were executed because the invasion fleet was struck repeatedly by storms and a major part engaged in a disastrous expedition to <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>. Other books from <PERSON> Guerin </PERSON>'s collection included <ORGANIZATION> King </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> XIV </ORGANIZATION>'s copy of <LOCATION> Racine </LOCATION>'s `` Esther,'' a tragedy celebrating the Sun King's generosity, the queen's devotion and religious harmony under his It appealed so much to <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> that he would attend rehearsals and follow the dialogue with his own gold - and leather-bound copy It sold for $ 59,320.
