<HEAD>Moscow Rejects NATO Report As `Propaganda Ploy'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A senior Soviet officer Tuesday rejected as a `` propaganda ploy'' a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> report saying the <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> massively outguns the Western alliance in conventional arms. `` This paper ... is not useful for the purpose of the future talks,'' Col.-Gen. <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Chervov </PERSON> told a news conference He referred to planned talks on conventional stability in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, for which a mandate is being negotiated in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> between the 16 <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and seven <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact nations. <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s 28-page report was billed by Secretary-General <PERSON> Manfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON> as an attempt to publicize relative East-West troop strengths and challenge <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to issue its data. <PERSON> Chervov </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> would publish its own figures at an unspecified date after consulting <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> allies. <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> report `` Conventional Forces in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>: The Facts,'' is not the basis for negotiators from the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> at the new conventional stability talks. But <PERSON> Chervov </PERSON> challenged this. The study focuses on the ground and air forces to be discussed at those talks and ignores naval forces that are not at issue. Diplomats in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> say they hope the talks, which will cover the territory from the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Ural </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>, will begin early next year. The <OR