<HEAD>Opinion Forums Want Defense Spending Cuts, Some Tax Hikes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Participants in a series of `` citizens assemblies'' held nationwide overwhelmingly favored cuts in defense spending, and most also supported selected tax hikes and more money for education, a public policy group reported Tuesday. Results of discussions at 13 of the special seminars involving a cross-section of 1,000 people were made public by the <ORGANIZATION> Roosevelt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> at a news conference Tuesday. The report, `` A Citizens' Agenda for the President,'' was sent to President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> last week. `` This is something like an X-ray of what the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> public might think if they really got into it and all the cards were on the table,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Higgens </PERSON>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Roosevelt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, which describes itself as a non-partisan public institute set up to `` make representative democracy work.'' The results, which showed the federal budget deficit as the major concern among participants, were obtained from forums held between Sept. 17 and Nov. 7. Those attending were nearly all at least high school graduates but had a wide variety of backgrounds. About half were Democrats, 30 percent Republicans and the remainder described themselves as independents, <PERSON> Higgens </PERSON> said. He said the center tried to make the groups as representative of all Americans as possible, but included only people who were willing to study 90 pages of objective briefing material and then participate in the day-long forums. <PERSON> Higgens </PERSON> acknowledged that the study could not be considered a scientific survey of public opinion, but organizers believe it accurately reflects the opinions people would have if they bothered to inform themselves on national issues. The assemblies are to meet again in May to assess <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s first 100 days in office and draw up a more extensive report for the president. On military spending, 44 percent of participants supported a 3 percent, across-the-board cut and 46 percent supported a 10 percent cut. Among the least popular expenditures were aid to resistance fighters against communist regimes, funds for anti-missile defenses and money to build up of conventional or strategic forces. `` In general, foreign aid and defense programs were ranked at a lower priority than all domestic programs,'' the report said. Seventy percent said foreign aid should be cut; 57 percent wanted cuts in <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> payments to physicians; and 52 percent said agricultural price supports could be reduced. Nearly all other suggested cuts in domestic programs received the support of less than half the participants. To further fight the deficit, 78 percent said tobacco, wine and beer could be taxed at higher rates, while 60 percent advocated a higher top personal income tax bracket of 33 percent, and more than half said they would support higher user fees for government services and gasoline tax hikes. Two-thirds also said business tax deductions could be limited, and more than half advocated a higher top corporate tax bracket. A majority of participants supported new federal spending on education, energy, environmental programs, civilian research and development, welfare reform and drug and crime prevention. Forums were held in <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Kalamazoo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>; the <LOCATION> Hickory-Unifour </LOCATION> area and the <LOCATION> Raleigh-Durham-Chapel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> area of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Manchester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Stockton </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cedar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rapids-Iowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>; and <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
