<HEAD>Four U.S. Teams To Search For MIAs, Talks Planned Between Sides</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has proposed talks with <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> regarding future cooperation in the search for American servicemen missing in action, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. The talks would take place following a 10-day joint search by four American and Vietnamese teams that starts Dec. 5, said spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> has agreed to a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> request to have four teams conduct the search, an increase from the two teams that were allowed to search various sites twice this year. `` We hope that this will enable us to make more rapid progress in efforts to obtain the fullest possible accounting of those still missing in action,'' <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> teams will consist of technical personnel from the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Casualty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Identification </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, he said. They will be investigating a number of cases in the areas of <PERSON> Vinh </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dong </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoi </PERSON>, south of <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>. `` We have proposed to the Vietnamese to meet in <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> following the conclusion of this activity, Dec. 19 to 21, to conduct technical talks, to review our joint activities to date and our future work program,'' <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said. `` We appreciate the increased cooperation of the government of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> in these efforts.'' <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> originally agreed to cooperate in the MIA searches for a 90-day period starting Sept. 1. The proposed talks would focus on extending that period. <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is `` hopeful that our joint cooperation will continue for as long as necessary to obtain the fullest possible accounting.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> says there are more than 2,400 Americans missing in action from the <LOCATION> Indochina </LOCATION> war, most of them in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has rejected demands from the impoverished <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> country that cooperation on the MIA issue be linked to the establishment of diplomatic links. But it has allowed American charitable groups to provide prosthetics and medical care for handicapped children. Trade with <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> is banned by law.
