<HEAD>Impaling May Have Saved Man's Life</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: first name Jakie is correct.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A construction worker fell three stories and was impaled on a 6-foot steel rod, but that probably saved his life, two doctors said. The heavy rod kept <PERSON> Jakie </PERSON> <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Klaber </PERSON> from plunging six more floors to the ground when it pierced his belly and groin, said Drs. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> and <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Zachariah </PERSON>, who treated <PERSON> Klaber </PERSON> at the scene Monday. `` The rod basically arrested his fall,'' said <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>. <PERSON> Zachariah </PERSON> said that without the rod, <PERSON> Klaber </PERSON> `` would have definitely gone over.'' <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said <PERSON> Klaber </PERSON> was lucid enough to answer routine questions about his medical history. `` Given the circumstances, he was relatively calm,'' <PERSON> Zachariah </PERSON> said. Firefighters cut the bar of concrete reinforcing rod and, with the rod still imbedded in <PERSON> Klaber </PERSON>'s body, lowered him to the ground in a basket. The rod was removed in surgery at <ORGANIZATION> Humana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital-University </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Klaber </PERSON>, 50, was in serious condition Tuesday with facial, abdominal and groin injuries following the accident at a parking garage being built by the <ORGANIZATION> Whittenberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Construction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. Witnesses and a <ORGANIZATION> Whittenberg </ORGANIZATION> vice president said <PERSON> Klaber </PERSON> was operating a crane from inside a control cab on top of the nine-story building. He was hoisting a half-ton wooden concrete-form panel when a wind gust apparently blew the 8-by-12-foot form into the wooden cab, knocking it and <PERSON> Klaber </PERSON> over the edge. `` My first thought was that the crane ... killed the man in the box,'' said <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON> Circuit Judge <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Corey </PERSON>, who watched from the nearby Hall of Justice. `` I could see that guy inside as it headed down.'' Still inside the control cab, <PERSON> Klaber </PERSON> fell headfirst 36 feet to the sixth-floor parking deck, which juts out farther than the top three floors. He fell almost vertically onto the steel rod, located within two feet of the garage's edge. The rod passed through some fat on <PERSON> Klaber </PERSON>'s abdomen and part of his groin, said Dr. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, director of university's emergency room
