<HEAD>Indiana Woman Helps Obtain Medical Treatment For Polish Child</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST CHICAGO, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A crippled Polish child on Tuesday entered a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> hospital, where she will be treated free of charge for birth defects, thanks to the efforts of a Polish-American woman. Seven-year-old <PERSON> Basia </PERSON> <PERSON> Rduch </PERSON>, who weighs just 20 pounds, flew to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> from her homeland Monday, accompanied by her mother, <PERSON> Daniela </PERSON>, a widowed seamstress from the village of <LOCATION> Godow </LOCATION>. The trip was made possible by the efforts of <PERSON> Terri </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, 35, of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` I feel very lucky,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Rduch </PERSON> said through a translator. `` I could n't ask for anything more. I have a lot of hope in my heart.'' The youngster was taken Tuesday to the <ORGANIZATION> Shriners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> for Crippled Children in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, where she will undergo tests for treatment for her birth defects, which include severe curvature of the spine. Her deformity makes it difficult for her to walk and causes digestive problems. After doctors in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> told Mrs. <PERSON> Rduch </PERSON> they could not help her child, she began efforts to get treatment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. She wrote to a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> hospital, but the letter did not have the correct address and was in Polish. She never received a reply. Mrs. <PERSON> Rduch </PERSON> did n't give up hope, however. In August, she gave a copy of that letter to a neighbor, who is Ms. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>'s cousin. `` My cousin sent me a copy of this letter and just asked me if I could take it up to the hospital,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, who speaks Polish and whose parents were born in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. But Ms. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> did n't stop there. She learned about the Shriners program of providing free care to needy crippled and burned children, and the charity's <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> hospital was contacted. Ms. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, a purchasing director for <ORGANIZATION> Specialty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Hammond </LOCATION>, also collected $ 3,500 in donations for <LOCATION> Basia </LOCATION>, most of it from Polish-Americans in northwestern <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. That money paid for the mother and daughter's trip.
