<HEAD>Reagan National Security Adviser Scoffs at Soviet Idea on Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s call for a `` Common European Home'' shared by the East and West is merely an attempt to preserve Soviet dominance over <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s national security adviser said Tuesday. In a speech prepared for a conference of the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Analysis </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Colin </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> said Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> should be praised for seeking reform in his country. But at the same time, <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, noting the 40th anniversary of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> in 1989, said this is no time for the West to let down its guard. As an example, he cited what <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> had proposed as a new structure in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in which `` all nations _ East and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> _ can live in peace and harmony.'' `` The Soviets assure us that there would be room in this house for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> as well,'' <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> said. `` We appreciate the assurance. But we did not ask for it, nor do we need it. We are in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, not at the invitation of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, but in alliance with our Western allies.'' <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, who likely will be returning to full-time duty in the Army when <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s term ends Jan. 20, asked his audience to consider what lies behind the Soviet call for a `` Common European Home.'' `` As I see it, it is an attempt to tie the future to the past, to freeze the ... European status quo,'' he said. <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> acknowledged that his conclusion `` may seem odd,'' given the Soviet pronouncements about a new era of political thinking, embraced in such terms of `` glasnost'' and `` perestroika.'' But <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> said he believes, nevertheless, that the Soviet proposal `` is an idea wedded to the past.'' `` Forty years after the Soviets imposed their presence in the middle of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' he said, `` the citizens of these countries still look to the West as their historical, cultural and political homeland. Their ferment today is a testament to the strength and durability of these aspirations.'' He also said the Soviets have `` rushed to construct a new home for all of us'' because the <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> allies of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> have, at last, moved `` to construct a European pillar'' of strength, challenging the Soviet goal of predominant power on the continent. `` If we analyze what this Soviet-built home would contain,'' he said, `` we find some very old ideas indeed _ unbalanced disarmament proposals, dissolution of military alliances, removal of foreign bases and acceptance _ yes, acceptance _ of the ideological division of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> presently enforced by Soviet power.''
