<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, the new <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> majority leader, first drew the nation's attention when he looked Lt. Col. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> in the eye and told him he had no monopoly on loyalty. `` Please remember ... that it is possible for an American to disagree with you on aid to the Contras, and still love God, and still love this country, just as much as you do,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> told the fervent <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> officer at the nationally televised Iran-Contra hearings. Although that moment represented something of a national debut for the <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> Democrat, he had already made himself a hero among fellow party members. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, as chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Campaign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, helped engineer the 1986 comeback that saw Democrats regain control of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, which they had lost in President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s 1980 landslide. His reward: instant clout on the Democratic side of the aisle and appointment as the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s deputy president pro tempore, an unexciting post but an important measure of the esteem in which he was held by his colleagues. Now, after an intensive backroom campaign launched after Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, announced last April he would step aside as majority leader, <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> has defeated two more senior colleagues to take the The losers were Sens. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON>, D-Hawaii and <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-La </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mitchell </PER