<HEAD>Conable Denounces Barriers to Third World Goods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 World Bank President <PERSON> Barber </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Conable </PERSON> on Tuesday denounced trade barriers that prevent Third World nations from selling their goods in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other industrial countries. <PERSON> Conable </PERSON> said aid to Third World countries was only half as much as they could earn if they were permitted to sell their goods freely to the donor countries. `` If you were to eliminate all international aid and all trade-distorting obstacles, you would have twice as a good a situation in terms of resource transfers for the developing world as you've got now,'' he said. <PERSON> Conable </PERSON> estimated the annual value of aid from all industrial countries at $ 35 billion a year, while their trade barriers prevented exports to them worth $ 60 billion. That was only the primary effect of the barriers, because additional trade would stimulate Third World growth, he added. `` The <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> countries alone have lost three quarters _ over $ 250 million worth _ of their annual sugar exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` In 1987 the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imposed anti-dumping actions on carnations -LRB- to limit imports -RRB- from <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>. All four exported only $ 16 million worth of cut flowers to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>; during that same year they paid almost 150 times that amount in interest to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commercial creditors,'' he in a statement he will submit next week in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> to a meeting of cabinet members of nearly 100 governments. The session will review progress toward dismantling trade barriers. <PERSON> Conable </PERSON> distributed blame widely. He noted that West European countries became the world's biggest exporters of beef and wheat while the share of the market supplied by <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>, two of the lowest cost producers, dropped sharply. He said the high price paid for rice to Japanese farmers, five times the world level, closed off sales by <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. The Third World's $ 1.2 trillion debt is not up for discussion in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Conable </PERSON> said it clearly is related to trade since whatever may be done about debt, the <ORGANIZATION> Third </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> will need to sell more goods. Three years ago, then-Treasury Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> proposed additional lending to Third World countries to help them grow out of their problems. Little additional lending has been forthcoming. More recently, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, whom President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has tapped as his secretary of state, has been promoting a `` menu of options'' under which debt may be reduced by agreement between creditor banks and debtor governments. `` You're getting an evolution of the so-called <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> plan,'' <PERSON> Conable </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> is the biggest source of international aid. The bank, owned by 151 countries, lends the Third World about $ 20 billion a year.
