<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> has proved himself tough and flexible, necessary qualities for dealing with the economic crisis and growing political opposition he will face after becoming president on Thursday. He is an economist with no experience in elective office, and at 40 will be <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s youngest president in half a century. That may be fitting, since more than half the nation's 84 million people are under 16. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> also has a disadvantage none of his predecessors has experienced: serious division within the <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which is known by its Spanish initials <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> and has governed <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> since 1929. In addition to being the youngest president in decades, <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> also is one of the best educated. He has two master's degrees and a doctorate in public administration, all from <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>, and speaks fluent English and French. The new president is short, trim and bald, dresses smartly and has a full black mustache that enhances an expression of half-puzzled wistfulness that often appears on his face. Friends who know him well, including political writer <PERSON> Adrian </PERSON> <PERSON> Lajous </PERSON>, say the genial, shy exterior hides a man of considerable ability and political savvy. As evidence, they offer the fact that he won the presidential nomination from a half-dozen older <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> rivals. As budget secretary under <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Madrid </PERSON>, the outgoing president, <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> revealed himself as a deft political infighter, excellent organizer and stickler for efficiency. `` He is very fast mentally,'' <PERSON> Lajous </PERSON> wrote recently. `` He plucks ideas out of thin air. His thinking is very sophisticated ... and it's a pleasure to watch him sparring.'' <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> is known as a demanding boss who expects things to run on time _ what Mexicans call `` American time'' rather than the less precise `` Mexican time.'' So greatly does the new president admire Japanese discipline that he sends his children to a school run by Japanese. He was born April 3, 1948, in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> but his family is from <LOCATION> Nuevo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Leon </LOCATION>, a northern industrial state. He married <PERSON> Cecilia </PERSON> <PERSON> Occelli </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> in 1972, seven years after they met at a dance, and they have three children: <PERSON> Cecilia </PERSON>, 14; <PERSON> Emiliano </PERSON> 12, and <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristobal </PERSON>, 9. A keen sportsman, <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> was a member of the Mexican riding association and the national equestrian team, winning a silver medal at the 1971 Pan American Games. He keeps fit by running and playing tennis and is an ardent soccer fan. Like his most recent predecessors, <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> rose through the ranks of the bureaucracy as a loyal <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> member. He comes from an old family of seasoned <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> politicians that settled in the small town of <LOCATION> Agualeguas </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Nuevo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Leon </LOCATION> in the 18th century, and joined the party at age 18. <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>, his father, has served in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and as commerce secretary. His mother, <PERSON> Margarita </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> <PERSON> Carvajal </PERSON>, is an economist and was active in party politics for many years. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s president is limited to a single six-year term and <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> faces problems that would have given some of his predecessors nightmares. An economic crisis has impoverished <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> since the bottom fell out of world oil prices in 1982. Enormous grass-roots support that kept the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> in power for two generations has diminished and the spendthrift days of the oil boom are gone. Payments on the $ 102 billion foreign debt have sapped development and prompted complaints the country's efforts to develop industry and increase exports serve only to pay Wall Street bankers. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> won narrowly in an election July 6 that was tainted by charges of fraud. The <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> won only 260 seats in the 500-seat <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>, compared with its customary 70 percent or more. The wishes of his predecessors often amounted to orders, but <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> will have to negotiate and compromise with opposition leaders who want to use public disaffection with the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> as a springboard for the 1994 election. Political analysts say the results last election's results indicate people are weary of the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION>'s high-handed ways and want a change. At a recent rally, <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> said the `` one-party'' era is over and the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> must learn to hustle for votes, but there were more charges of fraud in recent state elections. In speeches and interviews, <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> has said he will `` modernize'' <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, paring down the bureaucracy, getting rid of state-owned companies that lose money, fighting corruption, balancing the budget, reducing inflation, forcing export industries to become more efficient and reforming the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION>.
