<HEAD>Mexico at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mexico-Salinas Bjt</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Here are some facts and figures about <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>: THE LAND <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> shares a 2,062-mile border with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Its neighbors on the south are <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Belize </LOCATION>. It covers 761,064 square miles, about three times the area of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> is on the west, the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> on the east. The southern half is lush and tropical, the north arid. Much of the terrain is mountainous.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE PEOPLE <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has about 84 million people, roughly half of them under age 16, and 18 million of them live in the <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> metropolitan area. About 55 percent are of Spanish-Indian descent and 29 percent Indian. An estimated 90 percent are <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE ECONOMY Crude oil exports are the heart of the economy, but non-petroleum exports are growing rapidly. Sharply lower oil prices caused an economic crisis and the standard of living has been cut in half since 1982. Payments on the $ 102 billion foreign debt take money from development, a major problem for a nation that must create 1 million jobs a year just to keep up with population growth. The economy is a mixture of private enterprise and the government, which runs many industries, including oil through the monopoly <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' fourth biggest trading partner; the two-way exchange in 1987 was $ 35.1 billion. Inflation reached 159.2 percent in 1987 but has been reduced to less than 1 percent a month. The daily minimum wage is $ 3.50.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE GOVERNMENT <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has a federal, republican form of government with a 500-seat Chamber of Deputies and a 64-seat <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The president is elected every six years for a single term. The nation is divided into 31 states and the Federal District, part of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has governed since its founding in 1929. Relations with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are historically paramount and often tense. Many Mexicans still resent the loss of more than half the country's territory to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the first half of the 19th century.
</TEXT>
