<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> and the finance ministers of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s major allies will meet soon after President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> takes office in January, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government source said Tuesday. The source, who spoke only on condition of anonymity, said the session was planned to allow <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> to answer questions from his counterparts about the new administration's economic policies. The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday that a tentative plan for the meeting was outlined in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> two weeks ago at a meeting attended by Assistant Treasury Secretary <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulford </PERSON> and the deputy finance ministers of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. The seven countries, dubbed the Group of Seven, meet each year for economic summits. Finance ministers from the nations convene three or four times a year to further efforts to promote coordinated economic policies. The source said no dramatic announcements of policy changes would be coming from the post-inauguration meeting. `` The meeting is to give -LRB- <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> -RRB- a chance to reassure his counterparts of policies under a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration,'' the source said. The meeting is expected to take place in late February or early March. Both <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> have been forced since the election to reassure jittery financial markets that the new administration has no secret plan to drive down the value of the dollar as a way of curing the nation's huge trade deficits. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has insisted that as president he will pursue the same policy of coordinated efforts to stabilize the value of the dollar that the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has been pursuing since February 1987.
