<SECOND>AM-Insurance Insolvency,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>States Should Move Quickly To Close Insolvent Insurers, Study Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State regulators should move more quickly to liquidate insolvent insurers to minimize public harm and avoid costly failures similar to those that have hit the savings and loan industry, an insurance group recommended Tuesday. `` What we need today is a new determination by the regulators to act swiftly,'' said <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> McFadden </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brokers </ORGANIZATION>. `` In the real world, there are significant pressures which encourage regulatory delay rather than fast action against insolvent underwriters,'' <PERSON> McFadden </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> news conference. But `` the consequences for policyholders, regulators and insurers are far more severe than they would be if regulators acted quickly,'' he said. The study, `` Managing Insurer Insolvency,'' was prepared by <ORGANIZATION> Stewart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> NAIB </ORGANIZATION>. The association represents 58 international, regional and local firms that write more than 75 percent of the property-casualty insurance policies for business and industry in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` Many years ago, the mission -LRB- of regulation -RRB- was to prevent insolvencies. It was achieved by government support for cartel pricing which covered the costs of the weak,'' the study said. `` Keeping weak insurers afloat was an accepted cost of the cartel system.'' But <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, one of the study's authors and the former superintendent of insurance of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>, contended that `` insolvency is a result of regulation.'' <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said regulators operating on principles from the industry's `` cartel legacy'' too often focus on heroic rescues of insolvent insurers acting `` as a doctor who needs to keep the patient alive'' instead of allowing failing companies to go under. `` This wo n't get at the guts of the problem ... taking an insurance company out of the marketplace before it does something awful to save itself,'' <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, a co-author of the study, said changing liability rules, catastrophic coverage, insurance of the most risky situations and events and increased competition also were contributing to the worsening insurer insolvency problem. There have been about 58 property-casualty insurer insolvencies since 1983 according to the <ORGANIZATION> NAIB </ORGANIZATION>. Citing a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> investigation begun this fall into the failure of <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> _ which is estimated to cost $ 1.5 billion _ <PERSON> McFadden </PERSON> warned that investigations of other failed insurers will continue next year. `` There appears to be growing concern among federal policymakers that the insurance insolvency problem could parallel the savings and loan insolvency problem if regulatory policies remain unchanged,'' <PERSON> McFadden </PERSON> said. `` There are disturbing similarities in the insurance industry and <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls, where fraud and mismanagement resulted in the collapse of the system,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Chesson </PERSON>, counsel to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee overseeing the insurance insolvency investigations. <PERSON> Chesson </PERSON> said Mission's insolvency and two others the committee is investigating, <ORGANIZATION> Integrity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and the Los Angeles-based <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, represent `` the three largest failures ever in the history of insurance.''
