<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The hard-fought contest for <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> majority leader, marked by months of cajoling, concluded Tuesday in an aura of eloquence and cordiality. Maybe it was the hallowed walls of the Old Senate Chamber, used officially from 1810 to 1859, and still employed occasionally for secret meetings like this. Sens. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> sat together and chatted as they awaited the opening gavel of the third competitor, <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> conference </ORGANIZATION> secretary <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, the vice presidential nominee, won a standing ovation from his <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> colleagues and praise from nearly every speaker. And when the first ballot for majority leader put <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> one short of the 28 he needed to win, <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> and <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON> rose to their feet as one to call for a <ORGANIZATION> Mitchell </ORGANIZATION> victory by acclamation. `` It was extraordinarily cordial,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Rockefeller </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> `` There was not one instance of rancor or disconsonance `` There was no tension at all,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>. `` There were some extraordinarily good talks,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Wyche </PERSON> <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON>, D-Ga Seven people spoke on behalf of the three majority leader contenders _ two for <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, two for <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON> and three for <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>. `` I, of course, was the shortest,'' quipped <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON>, a <