<HEAD>Declaration Began International Chain of Political Events</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 30th `Arab nations' to UPDATE with debate
postponed</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES L. WATSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The immediate sequence of events leading to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> refusal of a visa to <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> began Nov. 15 in <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION>, when the <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> declared an independent state. They also issued a political statement widely interpreted as an implicit recognition of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and renunciation of terrorism, which would represent a significant move toward moderation by the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. Although the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> did not specifically recognize <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to exist, it accepted three <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> resolutions that do so. It did not say directly that terrorism would be abandoned, but committed the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> to the `` <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> declaration'' of 1985, which limits attacks to `` military targets'' in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the occupied territories. Military targets are not defined further. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> described it all as `` double talk'' that contained neither recognition nor a renunciation of terrorism. A nearly year-old rebellion against <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> occupation in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, which has cost the lives of more than than 300 Palestinians, provided the impetus for declaring an independent state. After the independence declaration and political statement were issued by the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, which acts as the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> legislature, <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> said the next move toward <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace was up to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has made recognition of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and renunciation of terrorism conditions for dealing tth the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration said the Palestinian statement contained `` positive elements'' but rejected the declaration of independence. It said the future of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> must be determined by negotiations with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, which captured them from <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> in 1967. Major sources of confusion about what the <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> said in the political declaration are its vague construction and the fact that it was issued only in Arabic. It says a `` comprehensive political settlement of the <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> conflict'' must be reached in a framework that includes `` <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> resolultions _ the last of which were <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Security Council Resolutions 605, 607 an 608,'' which denounce Israeli deportation of Palestinians from the occupied territories. As a category, <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> resolutions include the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>'s equating of Zionism with racism The <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> also called for an international peace conference `` on the basis of <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Security Council Resolutions 242 and 338,'' thus implicitly recognizing <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Resolution 242, passed in 1967, calls for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to withdraw from occupied territories in return for from territories occupied in the recent conflict in return for the `` right to live in peace within secure and recognized boundaries free from threats or acts of force.'' Resolution 338 provides for implementation of 242. In its declaration of independence, the council cited <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> Resolution 181 of 1947, which provides for separate Arab and Jewish states in <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION>. Many Arab and Islamic nations recognized the new <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state in the first days after it was declared, and Third World nations began to join the list. Western European governments generally approved what they described as the more moderate Palestinian position, but did not grant diplomatic recognition. Protests and strikes in increased among the 1.5 million Palestinians in the occupied territories. The Israeli army imposed curfews and other restrictions in an attempt curb celebrations of the independence declaration. On Nov. 16, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION> political declaration fell short of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> conditions for dealing with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>. Two days later, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> recognized the proclamation of an independent Palestinian state in a careful announcement that said full diplomatic ties were not included. When asked whether that amounted to recognition, the deputy foreign minister replied, `` In essence.'' The statement appeared to be an attempt to express continued support for the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> without alienating <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, with which <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> has become more cordial recently. <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, the only <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> nation to sign a peace treaty with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, recognized the new state on Nov. 20. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> also extended recognition on that day. <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> said on Nov. 22 the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had agreed to grant him a visa to address the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> during a debate on Palestinian issues scheduled to begin Dec. 1. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> said no application had been received. An English-language daily published in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reporter </LOCATION>, said Thursday that <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> had declared a moratorium on attacks on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> as part of the effort to promote the declaration of a Palestinian state. On Friday in <LOCATION> Tunis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION>, where the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> has its headquarters, it applied for a visa at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consulate. Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> issued a two-page statement the next day rejecting the visa request. He said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` has convincing evidence that <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> elements have engaged in terrorism against Americans and others.'' <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>, as <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> chairman, `` knows of, condones, and lends support to such acts'' and is `` an accessory to such terrorism,'' the secretary said. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> applauded the decision but was the only government in the world that did. Allies and friends of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> urged a change of heart. Critics even included the British government of Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's staunchest ally. A Foreign Office spokesman said: `` <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> would have liked to hear <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> confirm in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'' that the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> recognizes <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and `` has renounced terrorism.'' Arab nations said Monday the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> debate would be moved to <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> unless the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> granted the visa within 48 hours. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> said its decision was `` firm and final'' and consented to moving the meeting. On Tuesday, the assembly postponed the debate. A senior <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> diplomat said privately it probably would begin Dec. 13 or 14 in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Carl-August </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleischhauer </PERSON>, senior <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> legal counsel, said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was violating the 1947 U.S.-U.N. Headquarters Agreement, which requires the host country to provide visas for people invited by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. The agreement says `` federal, state or local authorities of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> shall not impose any impediments to transit to or from the headquarters district of representatives of members or officials of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, or of specialized agencies -LRB- or -RRB- representatives of non-governmental organizations recognized by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> for the for the purpose of consultation.'' In refusing the visa, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> relied on a paragraph in a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law passed on ratification, which is not part of the agreement. It says: `` Nothing in the agreement shall be construed as in any way diminishing, abridging, or weakening the right of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to safeguard its own security and completely to control the entrance of aliens into any territory of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> other than the headquarters district and its immediate vicinity ... and such areas as it is reasonably necessary to traverse in transit between the same and foreign countries.''
