<HEAD>Former Secretary Says Pentagon Already `Bankrupt'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON> called Tuesday for cancellation of a major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bomber project and two aircraft carrier groups to trim spending by an already `` bankrupt'' Pentagon. He said the budget will have to be cut $ 150 billion to $ 200 billion dollars over five years and the department, itself, restructured. <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON>, who was defense secretary from 1961 until 1968, said he sympathized with President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s unnamed choice to run the Pentagon. `` There is just no question about it,'' he told the <ORGANIZATION> Arms </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> at the private group's annual luncheon meeting. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is bankrupt. They have on contract and plan for contract more weapons than any reasonable level of a budget will support for the next five years.'' <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON> said cutting the budget and restructuring the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> `` is going to be one hell of a job, particularly if you do it without reducing security.'' In fact, he said, `` it's damn near impossible and perhaps politically impossible. You are going to have to cut two carrier groups, either the B-1 or B-2. You are going to have to do all kinds of things that are going to be politically unpopular.'' In his speech, <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON> urged completion of a strategic arms reduction treaty with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> designed to slash <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet arsenals of long-range nuclear weapons by 30 to 50 percent. `` The treaty can be completed in a year or less,'' he said. But, <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON> said, arguments raised against the treaty could cause the process to unravel. He cited the claim the cutbacks would make remaining <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> land-based intercontinental ballistic missiles more vulnerable to Soviet attack and that the numerical advantage in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> ground forces would pose a greater danger to <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` If the attacks continue they can prove to be decisive and we will lose the marvelous opportunity to reduce weapons and increase stability,'' <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON> said.
