<HEAD>Soviets Say Shuttle Performed `Brilliantly,' Longer Mission Planned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet space scientists declared a brilliant success the unmanned maiden voyage of the space shuttle Buran, and are planning a much longer second mission, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. `` The previous program was brilliantly performed; when the craft came to a halt on the runway its time deviation from the program reached only one second, while the deviation of the Buran's axis from that of the runway was only 1.5 meters,'' the official news agency reported. Only five of the 39,000 heat-protecting tiles broke away during the 3-hour, 20-minute flight Nov. 15 and the spacecraft, whose name means Snowstorm in Russian, successfully maneuvered in bad weather, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. It quoted Gen. <PERSON> German </PERSON> <PERSON> Titov </PERSON> as saying: `` We deliberately refused to postpone the launch and wait for ideal conditions. The value of the flight is that its program included the maximum sum of real and rather difficult tasks.'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the landing took place in relatively high winds and thick clouds. Officials have said the shuttle's second flight also will be unmanned. No precise information on its length was available. Cosmonauts on another Soviet space mission, a joint project including French cosmonaut <PERSON> Jean-Loup </PERSON> <PERSON> Chretien </PERSON>, began working aboard the orbiting space station Mir on Tuesday, a day after docking their Soyuz TM-7 capsule. <PERSON> Chretien </PERSON> will return with <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Titov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Musa </PERSON> <PERSON> Manarov </PERSON>, who have set an endurance record and will have been in space a full year when they make the descent Dec. 21. Commander <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Volkov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Krikalev </PERSON>, who went into space with the Frenchman, will remain on the Mir until April. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said one project, designed by French scientists, is to make a detailed study of the cardio-vascular system in space flight, using ultra sound to evaluate blood flow.
