<HEAD>Bowen: AIDS No Subject For Politics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The departing head of the federal health bureauracy urged his colleagues on Tuesday to keep AIDS from becoming a political issue as they attempt to build support for fighting the disease in the years ahead. `` We have treated AIDS simply and solely as the public health crisis it is,'' <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Otis </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> told a gathering of top federal officials involved in fighting the epidemic. `` Politically, our goal must be to build a consensus to keep the focus on public health,'' said <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON>. `` At the same time our political actions must be consistent both with the available knowledge and the proper protection of the public health, we also must take care not to make the AIDS crisis a referendum on lifestyles, or a chance to push liberal or conservative agendas.'' <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON>, a physician and former two-time governor of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, has stated that he plans to return to <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> and spend his retirement years tending his garden when a new administration takes over Jan. 20. His remarks to more than 200 federal officials convened for a two-day conference had the tone of an informal farewell to the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> troops engaged in the struggle against AIDS. `` People with AIDS should never be treated like political footballs or, on the other hand, political prizes,'' <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> told them. `` We must never broker the lives of people with AIDS for political advantage. `` Also the AIDS crisis is not to be viewed as a battlefield for career advancement or an opportunity to win awards,'' he said. Without naming names, <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> said some people `` have helped to foster deep divisions which are counterproductive and destructive to the cooperation and partnership necessary to successfully combat this epidemic.'' He said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration will face many difficult policy questions _ for example, whether distributing clean needles to addicts might be warranted in restricting the spread of AIDS, even though such a program `` may send the wrong message that drug use can be made safe.'' Another troublesome question is what to do about a pregnant woman who shares needles with other addicts infected with AIDS and thus threatens her baby with the infection, he said. `` What action should the state legitimately take to protect the baby?'' <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> asked. `` Here we have to balance rights and decide how far the state can go to protect a baby threatened by the virus.'' He said many other public health concerns are equally complex, `` but those in leadership positions are going to have to face up to these differences of opinion and make the tough choices.'' Losing sight of the need to keep public health policy separated from liberal or conservative political agendas `` opens the door to danger,'' said <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON>. For example he cited the work of scientists at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>. `` The <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people have long had a high regard for what's being done at <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION>, and rightly so,'' he said `` But what would happen if one political party twisted scientific information to meet a social agenda or to advance political fortune? Then, people would be justified in questioning the accuracy of that information, leaving doubt as to the real facts.'' He said there is already `` a temendous amount of denial now.'' `` Many people want to believe that they are immune to AIDS, or that somehow this ca n't happen to them,'' he said. `` If scientific information were altered to suit our own political purposes, we run the very real risk of creating even more doubt, dissension and disbelief. the ultimate result could be the continued spread of the virus, perhaps at an accelerated rate.''
