<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A toddler's abdomen was virtually replaced Tuesday in a rare five-organ transplant that doctors said was the 3-year-old girl's only chance for survival. Rolandrea Dodge of <LOCATION> Fruitland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, received a new liver, pancreas, stomach, small intestine and a portion of a large intestine. The young donor was not identified. <PERSON> Rolandrea </PERSON>'s spleen also was removed. `` The patient is doing fine,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Satoru </PERSON> <PERSON> Todo </PERSON>, who headed the surgical team at Children's Hospital of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Todo </PERSON> said the 16 -LCB- - hour operation, which is considered experimental, went smoothly except for one episode when the chilled organs inserted into her body lowered her temperature dramatically and her heart stopped beating for about a minute He said surgeons restarted her heart with cardio-pulmonary resuscitation techniques. <PERSON> Todo </PERSON> said <PERSON> Rolandrea </PERSON>'s heart was functioning normally following surgery, and she was moving her hands and legs. Her liver also was producing bile, a positive sign, he said. She was in critical condition in the hospital's intensive care unit after the operation, which ended at 3:40 p.m. Tuesday. `` The prognosis is very difficult to say, but I'm expecting it to go well,'' <PERSON> Todo </PERSON> said. Five organs have been transplanted simultaneously only once before. Last November, <PERSON> Tabatha </PERSON> <PERSON> Foster </PERSON>, 3 -LCB-, of <LOCATION> Madisonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, underwent the same operation at the same hospital. She died six months later of a blood infection. <PERSON> Tabatha </PERSON> survived longer than any of the other three people in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> who had abdominal transplants involving two or more organs. `` They -LRB- doctors -RRB- may have gone ahead with a little more confidence knowing how far <PERSON> Tabatha </PERSON> succeeded,'' said hospital spokeswoman <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardillo </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rolandrea </PERSON>, who is known as <PERSON> Rolly </PERSON>, was born with an incurable disease called intractable secretory diarrhea, which prevented her intestines from absorbing food and liquids. She had to be fed intravenously, although she was allowed occasional nibbles of candy, potatoes and other solid food. Aside from brief outings, <PERSON> Rolly </PERSON> has spent her entire life in hospitals. The girl's liver began failing about three months ago as a result of her high-protein intravenous feedings, and her skin became jaundiced. She received a pancreas and stomach in addition to intestines and a liver because it is easier to implant a large portion of the abdominal tract all at once. <PERSON> Rolandrea </PERSON> arrived in October to be evaluated for transplant. She was accompanied by her parents, <PERSON> Branden </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cyndi </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodge </PERSON>, who also have two sons. Her parents were with her before she went into surgery. Doctors in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> said she would n't survive long without a transplant. Doctors began administering an experimental drug Nov. 9 in hopes of allowing her intestines to absorb food and liquids, but it was unsuccessful, Ms. <PERSON> Cardillo </PERSON> said. `` That was really the last available treatment option,'' she said. Dodge, 27, a coal miner, said it was difficult deciding whether to allow the transplant, but `` it's the only hope that we've got left.'' `` We do n't have any doubts,'' he said. `` It's just the way our <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> people are. That's just the way they taught us, try not to think negative about things, it's going to work out.''
