<HEAD>Justice To Review DEA Drug Seizure Practices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday it will review a <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> practice of sometimes arranging for local police to make well-publicized seizures of drugs brought into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> under the control of <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> operatives. Associate Attorney General <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Keating </PERSON>, the No. 3 official in the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, plans to meet with <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> officials to discuss the matter, said <PERSON> Loye </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, a department spokesman. The meeting stems from a <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chronicle </ORGANIZATION> story Sunday which said the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> had arranged at least two drug seizures by state or local authorities in the <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> area to generate false news reports which would protect the identity of <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> undercover operatives. The undercover operatives sometimes pose as middlemen and ship loads of narcotics into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> druglords. The <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> on occasion then arranges for local law enforcement agents to seize the incoming drug shipments in an attempt to insulate the operatives from disclosure, said <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> sources, speaking on condition of anonymity. In addition to keep the drugs off the street, the practice also is designed to allow the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> to continue criminal investigations aimed at top-level narcotics figures, the sources said. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Seigenthaler </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Editors </ORGANIZATION>, said it is misleading to the press and public for the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> to initiate what becomes a highly publicized drug seizure by state and local police when the shipment has in fact been controlled by the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION>. `` I understand they have to find some way to protect the lives of the people and the security of the operation, but when they engage in subterfuge or creating situations that really do n't exist, they have to expect that sooner or later people are going to find out,'' said <PERSON> Seigenthaler </PERSON>. `` They have to find some other way to protect people and the security of the operation.'' In a statement, the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> said it is not the agency's policy `` to lie or mislead the media, nor is it our policy to misrepresent information to the media. No techniques have ever been used or will ever be used that are designed to out and out mislead or lie to the media or public.'' But `` to preserve the integrity'' of ongoing probes which often involve wiretaps, undercover operations and money laundering, and to assure that the highest level traffickers are eventually prosecuted, `` we can not release all of the details of these events as they occur,'' the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> statement added. The techniques used to prevent drugs from reaching market become public knowledge at the time of prosecution, the statement said. The <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chronicle </ORGANIZATION> cited an instance in 1984 in which <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> agents helped smuggle 952 pounds of cocaine into the country, then abandoned their van at a prearranged roadblock set up by the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> DPS </ORGANIZATION> alerted news reporters that troopers had found a cache of drugs which they described at the time as one of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>' largest seizures. A <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> case agent, describing the arrangement in testimony during a bond hearing for a man arrested in the operation, testified that `` we had a prearranged setup arranged with the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> where they would stage a traffic stop and seize the contraband.'' In a second instance, on Sept. 29 of this year, said the Chronicle, a load of cocaine was planted in an abandoned car and left to be discovered by deputies with the <LOCATION> Harris </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, sheriff's department, who notified reporters. <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> declined to discuss the Sept. 29 seizure, but denied that the cocaine had been planted in the car. <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> also denied that the agency had been in control of the Sept. 29 shipment.
