roke down. He said the campaign still owes between $ 1.5 million and $ 2 million. <PERSON> Welsh </PERSON> said that when lenders complained about non-repayment, the local campaign organizer who originally secured the money was to attempt to have the loan forgiven or a new schedule of payments worked out. But <PERSON> Welsh </PERSON> said the system did not work well, because some organizers never got back to the lender and others made an `` insufficient effort.'' In some cases, he said, lenders were told something would be done when no action was planned. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> asked Welsh if lenders were told in effect, `` the check is in the mail'' when no check had been issued. `` Yes,'' Welsh replied. Under cross-examination from <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> attorney <PERSON> Odin </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Welsh </PERSON> sought to distance <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> from day-to-day operations of his organizations. `` He is the founder and leading thinker, the primary person who defines broad policies ... general objectives and political goals,'' Welsh said. `` I do n't recall him involved in day-to-day financial operations.'' <PERSON> Welsh </PERSON> also told the jury that in September 1986 he launched `` Project Apollo'' to gain `` control of the loan situation.'' He said the project involved a combination of repayments, requests for forgiveness of loans and attempts to have promised interest rates lowered or payments stretched out. He said the operation came to a sudden halt when federal and state law enforcement authorities raided <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Leesburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, headquarters Oct. 6, 1986, and `` seized just about every scrap of paper having to do with any financial record.'' Despite the raid, <PERSON> Welsh </PERSON> testified, virtually all the 3,500 people with loans outstanding had been contacted and total debt by early 1987 was reduced by $ 1.5 million. In addition, <PERSON> Welsh </PERSON> said that in April 1987 the three main LaRouche organizations that owed lenders money were placed in involuntary bankruptcy, in a government action that froze the groups' financial transactions. The final disruption to the repayment campaign, <PERSON> Welsh </PERSON> said, came when several banks froze <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> organization accounts after it became public knowledge that a federal grand jury in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> was investigating the movement's financial dealings. <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> was indicted in October on 13 counts of mail fraud, conspiracy to commit mail fraud and conspiracy to defraud the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION>. The mail fraud counts stem from promissory notes and letters of credit sent through the mails by the LaRouche organization. Conviction on all counts could carry a maximum penalty of 65 years in prison and fines of $ 3.25 million for LaRouche. The six associates face lesser sentences if convicted of the mail fraud and conspiracy charges, which cover the years 1983 to 1987. In the tax conspiracy count, the federal grand jury charged that <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> has not filed a federal income tax return since at least 1979. On trial with <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> are his chief fund-raiser, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Wertz </PERSON>; his legal adviser, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Spannaus </PERSON>; and four fund-raisers: <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Billington </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Small </PERSON>, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON> and <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubinstein </PERSON>.
