<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Archaeology     11-29 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Archaeology,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Archaeologists Uncover Ancient Port</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL HIRSCHHORN_</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAIFA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Archaeologists have uncovered a Bronze Age port on the Israeli coast with a warehouse stocked with raisins, peas and olives dating to about 1,200 years before <PERSON> Christ </PERSON>, the director of the excavation said. Professor <PERSON> Michal </PERSON> <PERSON> Artzy </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Haifa </ORGANIZATION> said in an interview that the site uncovered at <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nami </LOCATION>, 12 miles south of the modern port city of <LOCATION> Haifa </LOCATION>, could be the oldest man-made port ever found. `` In that period, seafarers tended to hug the coast, and they used to come into port once every two days for food, so you needed ports along the shore at set stretches,'' she said. `` There is little reason for this site to exist, except as a port.'' Researchers found evidence a channel was cut between the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> and a river to form the port, Ms. <PERSON> Artzy </PERSON> said. She said the port appeared to date to at least 2000 B.C., but further research was needed to confirm the date. Objects uncovered in excavations begun last year include gold and silver jewelry, bronze sculptures and pottery from ancient civilizations, Ms. <PERSON> Artzy </PERSON> said. Ms. <PERSON> Artzy </PERSON>, who also serves on the staff of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Amherst </LOCATION>, was assisted on the dig last summmer by students from <LOCATION> Amherst </LOCATION> and from <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> A and M at College Station and <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Ithaca </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> Foodstuffs found in a warehouse were well preserved because a fire in about 1200 B.C. apparently caused a roof to collapse, blocking oxygen from reaching the food and damaging it, she said. `` We have whole examples of seeds and raisins, like your mother used to give you when you were a kid,'' Ms. <PERSON> Artzy </PERSON> said. The site apparently was abandoned after the fire and never resettled. She said artifacts found at the site indicated local residents were very wealthy and that the port was an international trading center. `` These were sea people with a lot of wealth,'' Ms. <PERSON> Artzy </PERSON> said. She added: `` Whether it was from piracy or this is simply a rich port, we do n't know.'' The pottery came <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, the ancient Greek states of Troy and <LOCATION> Mycenae </LOCATION>, and elsewhere, she said. She displayed other items that were found, including gold rings and earrings, a child's gold necklace, silver rings and a hand-crafted Egyptian ring. So many bronze items were found that archaeologists believe a bronze workshop may have existed at the site. Items include one bronze stand for incense burning that is decorated with pomegranates and another with the figure of a woman. `` These are especially valuable because they are unusually well preserved,'' she said. `` There was obviously a cult aspect to this, the woman's body and the pomegranate, perhaps a fertility cult.''
</TEXT>
