got along well with <PERSON> Eitan </PERSON> and had a lot of confidence in what he was going to do for him,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Nishnic </PERSON> said, adding that <PERSON> Eitan </PERSON> had met with <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> a week ago. An attorney who previously represented <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Gill </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>, said he hoped police would investigate the death `` to see if there was any foul play. `` I'm not suggesting there is or would be or was. But I do think that would have to be explored,'' <PERSON> Gill </PERSON> said by telephone from <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>. A defense witness, Swedish-born <PERSON> Anita </PERSON> <PERSON> Pritchard </PERSON>, tried to commit suicide by slitting her wrists and swallowing tranquilizers on Aug. 21, 1987, after her testimony was discredited during the trial. <PERSON> Eitan </PERSON> served for 17 years as a <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> district court judge before retiring in 1983. His joining the defense was widely viewed in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> as adding prestige to the team. He is survived by his wife, who lives in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, and two children.
