<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Joffrey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ballet </ORGANIZATION> founder <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Joffrey </PERSON>, who died earlier this year, was recalled for his enthusiasm, good taste and love of the dance on Tuesday at a memorial service at the City Center, where his company performs. Among the speakers was choreographer <PERSON> Agnes </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mille </PERSON>, who praised <PERSON> Joffrey </PERSON>'s attention to details in recreating lost ballet masterpieces. `` Bob had a strange reverence, curiosity and fervor for the works of other masters, like a museum curator. He introduced them to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. This is a gift to our time, to our culture, and <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> did it,'' Miss <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mille </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Kitty </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlisle </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> on the Arts, said that the <LOCATION> Joffrey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ballet </LOCATION> performed nearly 200 ballets in 32 years, about half of them created for the company. Other speakers mentioned that the company was the first to commission modern-dance choreographers to create for it. It was the first to have residences in both <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. A ballet that <PERSON> Joffrey </PERSON> choreographed, `` Astarte,'' was the first ballet pictured on the cover of Time magazine. The last ballet he choreographed was the full-length `` The Nutcracker,'' which premiered in 1987. Reconstructions for the company include `` Parade,'' by <PERSON> Leonide </PERSON> <PERSON> Massine </PERSON>, `` The Afternoon of a Faun'' by <PERSON> Vaslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Nijinsky </PERSON>, `` The Green Table'' by <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PE