oalition of <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>. `` His -LRB- <PERSON> Vaughan </PERSON>'s -RRB- willingness to undergo imprisonment, even for this short a time, provides a tremendous boost for our efforts,'' <PERSON> McMonagle </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Vaughan </PERSON>'s stand also was praised by <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, archbishop of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, in a letter Sunday to the bishop. `` What you do today you do for all of us who want with all our hearts to do the same but are not free to do so at present,'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said, telling <PERSON> Vaughan </PERSON> his example `` will give courage to thousands of other mothers to choose life, however difficult the choice.'' Besides <PERSON> Vaughan </PERSON>, those released after serving the two-day sentence were <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> <PERSON> Starrs </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Parkesburg </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Willsher </PERSON> of Reading; the Rev. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Doron </PERSON>, pastor of the non-denominational Church of the New Covenant in <LOCATION> Marlton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Priscilla </PERSON> <PERSON> Gossens </PERSON> of Beechwood, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>; the Rev. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tarrytown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>; and <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Billington </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Glassboro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J </LOCATION>.
