<HEAD>Newspaper Photographer Helps Police Nab Absent-Minded Robber</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNT STERLING, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An absent-minded robber who left his gun inside a bank during a hold-up and locked himself out of the building was tracked by a newspaper photographer, who ordered him to `` stop or I'll shoot.'' Photographer <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Warner </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> was near the Montgomery-Traders branch bank and heard the robbery report on his police scanner, Officer <PERSON> Joni </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Mount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sterling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> followed the robbery suspect, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> of <PERSON> Carlisle </PERSON>, and pointed out the man's location when she and a deputy sheriff arrived after the Monday morning robbery in this eastern <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> town, <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said. The photographer said he followed the man to prevent his escape but also had wanted to find a way to coax him to turn around for a picture. `` I stood behind a telephone pole and I said, ` Stop or I'll shoot,''' <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> said `` And I did shoot him, I shot his picture.'' <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> said the man did not stop but continued running up a hill. When Ms. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> arrived, <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> said he yelled and pointed in the direction of <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, then took photographs as police made the arrest. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, 34, was charged with first-degree armed robbery. He was held in lieu of a $ 25,000 full cash bond Tuesday in the <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Regional Jail. The robber had forced his way into the bank shortly before it opened by holding a woman employee at gunpoint near the back door, Ms. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said. He forced another female employee to unlock the vault and had both workers fill a duffel bag with money. Afterward, he made them lie on the floor while he tied their ankles together with duct tape, Ms. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said. The robber also took the car keys of one of the women. `` While he was tying them up, he laid his gun on a pop machine. His mistake _ he left it laying there'' when he went outside to put the money in the woman's car. `` He forgot that the -LRB- bank -RRB- door would lock behind him, and he could n't get back inside.'' By then, a third employee was arriving at the bank, and the suspect tried to get that employee to let him back inside, but he refused. `` He told him that he had robbed the bank. ... He went to the woman's car and got the money out of it, and he started walking off,'' Ms. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said. The suspect was arrested soon afterward. <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> said a picture he shot of the arrest ran on the weekly newspaper's front page this week and more photos appeared inside.
