<HEAD>Rift Among Palestinian Factions Over Strike Observance</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS two grafs with settlers launching highway patrols</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Israeli soldiers in the occupied lands wounded 20 Palestinians Tuesday, hospital officials said, and merchants were caught between one faction demanding a strike and another insisting they stay open. Among the wounded were a 10-year-old boy shot in the leg and a 14-year-old hit in the chest, the Arab hospital officials said. More than 7,000 Palestinians have been wounded in a year of rebellion against Israeli occupation of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. At least 316 have been killed and 11 Israelis have been slain. Gangs of young Islamic extremists and <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> activists armed with knives and clubs marched through <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> on Tuesday, shouting threats at each other and issuing conflicting orders. Members of <ORGANIZATION> Hamas </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- Zeal -RRB- sprayed a warning to merchants on walls in Islamic green: `` Today is a strike day. Be sure you observe it.'' Followers of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> kicked on closed doors, shouting to store owners that they would be protected from <ORGANIZATION> Hamas </ORGANIZATION> if they opened. The strike was widely observed in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Hebron </LOCATION>, a predominantly fundamentalist <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> town, was completely shut down. Army commanders strengthened patrols and imposed curfews on more than two dozen refugee camps, towns and villages. At least 370,000 of the 1.5 Palestinians in the territories were confined to their homes. At the root of Tuesday's factional conflict was a disagreement between <ORGANIZATION> Hamas </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Fatah </ORGANIZATION> faction of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> over the proclamation Nov. 15 of an independent Palestinian state. The declaration is based on a 1947 <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> partition plan that called for both <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> and a Jewish states in <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Hamas </ORGANIZATION> rejected it and called a protest strike for Tuesday, the 41st anniversary of the partition plan. The Unified National Leadership of the Uprising, backed by the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>, did not call for a strike. In a recent leaflet, <ORGANIZATION> Hamas </ORGANIZATION> leaders said: `` How is it possible to think that Jews want a just peace? The Jew is a Jew, regardless of the party he belongs to.'' Three masked <ORGANIZATION> Hamas </ORGANIZATION> followers in <LOCATION> Jericho </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> town, flagged down Arab-run buses en route to <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> and forced them to turn back, <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> witnesses reported. The young men entered the buses and shouted at the drivers: `` Go back! Go back!'' Stores were closed in <LOCATION> Ramallah </LOCATION>, north of <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>. One shopkeeper told reporters other merchants complied after being threatened by <ORGANIZATION> Hamas </ORGANIZATION> loyalists. An elderly man later advised him: `` Do n't tell these things to outsiders.'' Another group urging a strike Tuesday was the pro-Syrian Popular Front for the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION>, which also rejected the independence declaration. Palestinian leaders expressed concern about the growing rift and said it might harm the uprising in the territories <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> captured from <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> in 1967. `` We know about the risk of this confrontation. We are working to stop it,'' said <PERSON> Sufian </PERSON> <PERSON> Khatib </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> surgeon whose views have been identified with those of the Popular Front. <PERSON> Khatib </PERSON> also said the coinciding strike calls did not indicate a new alliance between fundamentalists and hardline <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> factions opposed to even implicit recognition of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. `` We have some points in common but we are not together in the field,'' he told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. Another Palestinian official said the independence declaration by the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, which acts as the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> legislature, had wide support in the occupied lands. `` A majority of the Palestinian people are behind the <ORGANIZATION> PNC </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdul-Hadi </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestinian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> for the Study of International Affairs. Armed Jewish settlers in the northern <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> launched highway patrols on Tuesday to protect Israeli drivers from being stoned by Palestinians. Three cars patrolled the roads, each bearing a large Israeli flag, said organizer <PERSON> Yacov </PERSON> <PERSON> Eshel </PERSON>. He said soldiers stopped one car at an army checkpoint near the Palestinian town of <LOCATION> Qalqiliya </LOCATION> and told the driver he could not enter unless he removed the flag. The driver refused, and was turned back.
