<HEAD>A Plan For Stock Market Liquidity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 What this market of corporate stocks needs is liquidity, said the professor, and he went on to suggest that the corporations themselves consider providing it. The professor's observation has its origins in the debacle of Oct. 19, 1987, when the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average dropped hundreds of points in a few hours, devouring about one-half trillion dollars of value. Now that's illiquidity, said the professor. There were sellers everywhere and almost no buyers, and many of the specialists, who are supposed to buy when others are selling, were swamped by the avalanche. It could have been worse, says Professor <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON>. In fact, it would have been worse if companies had n't used their own cash to buy back their own stocks. He feels they helped turn a tide that could have destroyed the market. Observing those actions, the professor developed a detailed plan to eliminate excess volatility in securities markets by asking listed companies to establish permanent stabilization funds. These funds would remain on the sidelines, invested in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Treasury notes, until they were needed. And that need would be determined by a precipitous drop in stock prices. <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON>, who teaches economics and finance at <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, would have the companies enter the market to buy a preset number of shares when the price of their shares fell to a certain level. He offers this example: <ORGANIZATION> XYZ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has 100 million shares outstanding at an average share price of $ 52.50. It decides to stabilize prices by buying 100,000 shares if the price drops $ 2.50 to $ 50 a share ... and sell 100,000 shares in a comparable rise. The transactions would be triggered only when the price rose or fell by an increment of $ 2.50. If the efforts failed to stabilize prices then the company would be prepared to buy another block at $ 47.50 or sell at $ 57.50. The company would be prepared to buy shares at each $ 2.50 increment down to a total price drop of $ 30 a share. For <ORGANIZATION> XYZ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, this would require a stabilization fund of a little more than $ 42 million. <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON>, author of the recently published `` Equity Markets: Structure, Trading and Performance,'' justifies his thesis by stating that the only way to stabilize a market is to commit capital to market making. The result of his plan, he says, would be more stable markets, increased investor confidence and perhaps a bonus for the corporations. He explains that the stabilization funds themselves might generate positive cash flows because participating companies would realize gains from routine buying and selling at certain price intervals. In effect, they would emulate the work of the successful specialists, making their profits from the spread between bid and asked prices. Should such a plan work, it might encourage individual investors to return to the market, which they fled in droves after _ and some smart ones before _ the October 1987 debacle. One of their main fears has been volatility. <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON>, whose proposal was published in the fall 1988 issue of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Portfolio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>, believes the stock market remains overly volatile because of insufficient liquidity. He suggests that the liquidity added by the corporations themselves would serve to mitigate sharp moves in at least two ways, first by the infusion of money, and then by assuring owners to hold firm rather than dump. To avoid any corporate manipulation of stocks, he would allow the buy and sell orders to be entered only upon market openings and re-openings, and would have exchange officials supervise the transactions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday Nov 30</NOTE>
