<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> oil ministers have ended nearly two weeks of tense discussions with a formal agreement to limit production and pump prices back toward the cartel's benchmark of $ 18 per barrel. But before the day was out, one oil minister indicated Monday that his new quota was not official, causing futures prices to back off after a sharp runup. The accord, which ended the winter meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION>, set an output ceiling of 18.5 million barrels a day for the 13 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members, well under the 22.5 million that analysts estimate the cartel currently is pumping.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks have boosted their prime lending rates a half percentage point to 10.5 percent, the highest level since mid-1985. The increase announced Monday will mean a jump in rates on a variety of consumer loans pegged to the prime, including home-equity loans. It also will raise borrowing costs for many companies that rely on banks for financing.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The imbalance between what <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> imports and sells abroad narrowed to $ 28.53 billion in the July-September quarter, a 5.4 percent decline, the government reports. It was the third straight quarterly drop. Through the first nine months of the year, the deficit is running at an annual rate of $ 125.2 billion, compared with last year's record $ 160.3 billion deficit, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Monday
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm export volume hit a 6-year peak of 147.5 million metric tons in the year ended Sept. 30, with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> again the biggest customer, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agricultural exports climbed to $ 35.2 billion this past year, while imports of farm products rose to a record $ 21 billion, the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. That left the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> with a net agricultural trade surplus of $ 14.2 billion for fiscal 1988, compared with $ 7.22 billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade negotiators have agreed to extend through 1990 an agreement calling for the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to buy at least 9 million metric tons of grain a year from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The 27-month extension signed Monday in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> revived a five-year pact that expired Sept. 30.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal savings and loan regulators have proposed an `` early intervention'' plan allowing the government to take over a failing institution before it becomes insolvent. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, which oversees the nation's 3,028 federally insured S & amp; Ls, also proposed Monday regulations requiring institutions with riskier commercial and stock investments to hold more capital, or reserve funds, than institutions investing mostly in residential mortgages, the traditional mainstay of the thrift industry
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Speculators have bid <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s stock higher on the hunch that fattened offers would emerge in the unprecedented auction for the food-and-tobacco giant, which has lured price tags as high as $ 26.8 billion. Monday's price rise came as a company-imposed deadline for a second round of bids approached today for the biggest corporate takeover ever.
