<FIRST>r f PM-Britain-Economy Bjt   11-29 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Economy, Bjt,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government's Policies Questioned As Economy Flounders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Beset by resurgent inflation, high interest rates and a record trade deficit, the British economic rebound that eight months ago was considered a miracle has turned into a problem for Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>. In March, <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> was hailed as an economic wizard who had cured the British disease of high inflation, high unemployment and high interest rates. But last week, government figures showed the current account deficit had quadrupled to 2.43 billion pounds _ about $ 4.5 billion _ in October. The news prompted British banks to boost interest rates for the ninth time since June, rattling the stock market and raising the prospect of higher borrowing costs for consumers and industry. Now, the government's policies and <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>'s political future are being questioned, not only by such traditional critics the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> but also by some members of <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>'s own <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. `` With Conservative MPs -LRB- Members of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- grumbling about soaring mortgage costs and Labor convinced that the government at last is vulnerable over the handling of the economy, the gossip at <LOCATION> Westminster </LOCATION> has reached a fevered pitch,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> wrote recently. <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> is defending his strategy of using higher interest rates to choke off inflation, which Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> says is her top economic priority. But critics say the strategy does not yet appear to be working, is a painful way to cure <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s economic ills and could lead to a recession. Critics say the economic ills stem from the consumer boom sparked partly by tax cuts that <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> announced in March. The sweeping tax cuts reduced the top income tax rate from 60 percent to 40 percent and the base rate from 27 percent to 25 percent. The higher interest rates are intended to fight inflation by discouraging that consumption, which fuels inflation and attracts imports, and to squeeze corporate profits by boosting the pound, thus discouraging inflationary pay raises. But the higher rates, which some economists say must go even higher before they will work, also mean a stronger pound, which hurts exports. Higher rates also boost mortgage costs, which helps increase inflation. Some economists say inflation, which was 3.3 percent in January, will top 8 percent. <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> believes it will peak at 7 percent next year before falling back. The annual inflation rate now is about 6.4 percent. On Friday, addressing <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION> businessmen, <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> said the interest rate hike was `` a clear indication that this government is not prepared to take any risks with inflation.'' But he added: `` Interest rates do take time to have their full effect.'' <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> came under particularly sharp attack last Friday when the government announced the huge current account deficit. The ensuing interest rate increase brought the benchmark interest rate to 13 percent, its highest level in more than 3 -LCB- years. Stock prices plunged more than 2 percent Friday, and dipped another 0.7 percent on Monday, as measured by the <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> 100-stock index. It marked the latest November turmoil for <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>, who with five years as <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> head has held the office longer than any other since World War II. In his Nov. 1 autumn statement, an annual speech which is part of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s budgetary process, Lawsons new economic forecasts were sharply at odds with his previous predictions. Two weeks later, journalists quoted him as suggesting restricting government benefits for the elderly. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> denied the reports, but when challenged to check its tape recording of the remarks said its tape machine had malfunctioned. Conservative <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Biffen </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> minister, said on <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION> television that <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> `` clearly has a problem of confidence'' and suggested he was in `` a very exposed position.'' The Financial Times discounted speculation that <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> was about to fall from grace, saying: `` The chancellor's misfortunes are in part simply a reflection of the unsustainable heights to which he was elevated earlier this year and of the notorious fickleness of some MPs and political commentators.''
