<HEAD>Dollar Inches Up, Stocks Surge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar rose slightly against the Japanese yen today, and share prices sharply rebounded on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The dollar closed at 122.15 yen, up from Monday's close of 122.00 yen. The currency opened higher following its advance overnight in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, then gradually slid back. Sources said the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> bought dollars to stabilize the currency when it was about to fall below the 122-yen mark in the early afternoon. The central bank does not comment on its activities. Dealers attributed the dollar's rise in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to the increase Monday in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> prime interest rate from 10 percent to 10.5 percent, and the agreement by the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> to reduce production. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members meeting in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> agreed to a daily production quota of 18.5 million barrels and a target price of $ 18 a barrel. The announcement triggered a $ 1-a-barrel increase in oil prices. But Finance Minister <PERSON> Kiichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON> said the agreement's effect on exchange rates was mostly psychological and it would not immediately affect the world economy. <PERSON> Mitsuhiko </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinugasa </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Daiwa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> said the dollar fell after its initial jump because speculators in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> had expected an increase in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> prime rate and its occurrence did not change market sentiment for a weaker dollar. `` Many market players still tend to think they should get rid of the dollar now,'' <PERSON> Kinugasa </PERSON> added. An exchange dealer with the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION>, speaking anonymously, said other traders were awaiting the release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> gross national product figures for the July-September period, due later today, and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> unemployment figures for November, expected on Thursday. Meanwhile, the 225-issue <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> regained 334.98 points, or 1.2 percent, to return to 29,318.30. On Monday, the index dropped 380.27 points, its largest one-day decline since Sept. 1. The index gained 79.53 points shortly after trading began Tuesday and advanced further in the afternoon, boosted by the stabilized currency market, dealers said. Volume on the first section was estimated at 1.1 billion shares in active trading.
