<HEAD>Professor's Economic Reform Proposals For China Reach The Top</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An American professor who drafted proposed economic reforms for <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> officials said he expected little more than a handshake and photograph when he was summoned to meet with General Secretary <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON>. But <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hsiao </PERSON>, 53, a professor of economics and finance at <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Connecticut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, found himself engaged in a frank discussion with the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader. The meeting lasted nearly 90 minutes and was reported on the front pages of Chinese newspapers and on television. The meeting occurred while <PERSON> Hsiao </PERSON>, a native of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> who has lived in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> since 1960, was visiting the <LOCATION> Hunan </LOCATION> province late this summer under the auspices of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Hsiao </PERSON> was touring a railroad car factory when he received word that he was wanted in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, but he did not learn until after his arrival in the capital that it was <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> who wished to speak with him. `` I thought it would be just 10 minutes _ shake hands, take your picture,'' he said Monday. Before leaving the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hsiao </PERSON>, the founder and former dean of <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Connecticut </ORGANIZATION>'s business school, had mailed a copy of his economic proposals to Chinese leaders, not quite sure who would read the 17-page document. In case officials did not want to read the whole thing, he included a two-page summary. <PERSON> Hsiao </PERSON> said it was clear from his conversation with <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> that the Chinese leader had read the entire document. `` That impressed me the most,'' he said. `` He was very interested.'' <PERSON> Hsiao </PERSON> said he was told to speak his mind, and that the exchange `` sounded like a normal discussion between two economists.'' `` Basically I proposed that some state-run enterprises ultimately should be given to the people,'' said <PERSON> Hsiao </PERSON>. Production would increase if people were made responsible for a company's profits and losses, he said. Under the current system, he said, there is no incentive to go beyond quotas, and nobody is accountable because `` no one is the boss.'' Although private enterprise is permitted on a limited basis in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hsiao </PERSON> said he told <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> that the government should take action to promote such activities. Entrepeneurs now proceed cautiously, he said, because they fear state intevention. <PERSON> Hsiao </PERSON> also recommended that local government adopt rules and regulations protecting the property rights and interests of private owners. According to <PERSON> Hsiao </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> leader agreed that provisions should be adopted to promote private enterprise. <PERSON> Hsiao </PERSON> also quoted <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> as saying that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is already moving in the general direction he proposed, but that the government's actions must take into account society's ability to bear radical reforms. `` <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> believes that there is only so much that society can absorb at a time,'' <PERSON> Hsiao </PERSON> said. The professor said he is cautiously optimistic that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> will be able to solve its economic problems. Unlike the situation in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, he said, `` people in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> are fully aware that their future is tied to the success of economic reform.''
</TEXT>
