<HEAD>Commuter Trains, Buses Disrupted; Army Ordered to Help</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Strike-bound suburban commuters crowded into scarce buses or drove their cars on jammed expressways today, while the government ordered out army trucks to move stranded passengers. The strike called by the Communist-led <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Confederation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> halted all trains on two of the four regional express networks and disrupted subway and bus routes. The first army vehicles were expected to arrive in the capital late today with as many as 400 expected to be on hand for Wednesday morning's rush hour, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said. Transport Minister <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Delebarre </PERSON> announced the military intervention on national television Monday night and accused the union of waging `` a sort of union guerrilla warfare of harassment. This is not in the French union tradition.'' <PERSON> Delebarre </PERSON> said strikers blocked buses in their terminals, flattened tires and sabotaged engines. The transit agency's management was being ordered to stop paying striking workers and to start disciplinary proceedings against lawbreakers, he said General Confederation of Labor Secretary-General <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Krasucki </PERSON> said on French radio today that the government was mistaken if it planned to solve the labor dispute `` with police, troops or military trucks.'' At midday today, the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> regional transit agency reported the regional A and B lines halted, only 60 percent of buses operating and service reduced by up to 25 percent on some subway lines. Premier <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON>'s Socialist government has been hit by striking nurses, postal employees, government office workers and other public service employees demanding wage increases that <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> says would be inflationary. `` The real motive of these strikes is political,'' the conservative newspaper <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Figaro </PERSON> said in today's editorial. `` The Communists are trying to exert unbearable pressure on the Socialists with a view toward the municipal elections of next March.'' The Communist share in recent French elections slipped to less than 10 percent of the total vote. But the party appears to see a chance to grab the role of the only authentic leftist force, as the Socialists continue the economic policies of the conservatives who controlled the government from 1986 until last May. <PERSON> Krasucki </PERSON> dismissed repeated suggestions that the strikes were intended to increase Communist chances in next year's municipal elections as `` completely stupid.'' His union is demanding increased safety measures and across-the-board pay increases of $ 170 a month. The transit authority Sunday offered raises of $ 42.50 a month. A typical transit worker earns a top-scale monthly wage of $ 1,400. The two regional express lines paralyzed since Monday usually carry more than 600,000 of the roughly 10 million people who commute to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> by bus, train or car.
