<HEAD>Third Quarter GNP Revised Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS New 6th graf, The Commerce Department ..., to UPDATE
with report on corporate profits. Picks up 6th graf pvs, In another
...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's economy grew at a moderate 2.6 percent annual rate in the third quarter, tempered by the summer drought, the government reported today. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the performance of the gross national product, the broadest measure of the economy, slowed in the July-September period after expanding at an annual rate of 3.2 percent during the first six months of the year. It was the slowest pace since the fourth quarter of 1986, when the economy grew at a sluggish 1.4 percent rate. The department said that without the drought third-quarter growth would have been a strong 3.2 percent. The report, however, represents an upward revision from a preliminary estimate last month, which pegged growth at 2.2 percent. The revisions were about in line with economists' expectations and fit in with anticipation in the market that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> will soon move to curb inflation by dampening growth with higher interest rates. Major banks raised their prime lending rates on Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> also reported today that corporate profits rose a slight 0.2 percent in the third quarter, to $ 163.1 billion, the worst performance since a loss in the last quarter of 1987. In another report Monday, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the imbalance between what the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> imports and exports narrowed to $ 28.53 billion in the July-September quarter, a 5.4 percent decline. It was the third straight quarterly drop. Through the first nine months of the year, the deficit ran at an annual rate of $ 125.2 billion, compared with last year's record $ 160.3 billion deficit. Analysts predicted the deficit for all of 1988 should be at least 20 percent lower than 1987, marking the first time since President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> took office in 1981 that the trade deficit has improved. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> policymakers have relied heavily on the dollar's decline in value over the last three years to increase exports by making them more affordable abroad, and thus help ease the trade deficit. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report suggested the strategy has been at least partly successful, easing some pressure for the dollar to decline more. Another event that helped the dollar Monday was an Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries accord aimed at limiting production and raising the price of oil, which often is priced in dollars. Higher <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> prices raise demand for dollars to pay for the oil. The <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> pact reached in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, was viewed skeptically by many industry analysts, given the cartel's history of violating its own agreements, but it still pushed oil prices up more than $ 1 to the $ 15-a-barrel level. Meanwhile, major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks boosted their prime lending rates a half percentage point to 10.5 percent, the steepest level since mid-1985 and the fourth rise this year. The prime rate rise had been widely expected, but some analysts said it also contributed to a strengthened dollar, which rose in value against the Japanese yen, British pound, West German mark and other key currencies. The dollar's strength helped the bond market, where the 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond rose about $ 2.50 per $ 1,000 in face amount and its yield fell to 9.14 percent from 9.17 percent Friday. But the impact was hardly felt on <LOCATION> Wall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION>, where the numbers of gaining and losing issues were about even in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Stock Exchange trading. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 6.76 to 2,081.44, and broader market indicators were mixed.
