<FIRST>d f PM-AutoIncentives     11-29 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Incentives,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Inventories, Production Increases Mean New Incentives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN L. ADLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The math is simple: when too many new cars are built and too few are sold, incentives result. Auto analysts say the latest round will arrive in time for Christmas. `` We're going to have to have some type of programs,'' analyst <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillippi </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> said Monday. `` The companies would much rather give away part of the gross profit than cut production.'' Auto giant <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> may have a 100-day backlog of cars by the end of December, an inventory nearly 50 percent larger than considered comfortable. `` If you just look at the recent reactions of the car companies to inventory bulges, it's obvious they will do something,'' <PERSON> Phillippi </PERSON> said. `` Incentives of varying proportions and programs have been part of the landscape for four years now.'' Each of the Big Three have incentives in effect. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s incentives programs have no set expiration; many of <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s programs are set to expire Dec. 5, while some <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> programs expire <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, in the best shape of the Big Three as far as inventories go, plans to build more cars in the first quarter of 1989 than it announced two weeks ago. Its latest production schedule for the first three months of 1989 shows 501,000 cars to be built compared with 475,000 announced a few weeks ago. `` In the case of <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, it is losing some sales because of a lack of certain models, especially the Probe and the <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> of <PERSON> Drexel </PERSON> <PERSON> Burham </PERSON> <PERSON> Lambert </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` That's an up side, but there's not very much good about this.'' <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> has begun trimming some first quarter production schedules, <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> said. Whether the incentives will take the form of cash, interest rate discounts or other, more exotic lures is a closely guarded industry secret. `` They've got a bookshelf full of these programs, guys whose only job it is to dream up new programs,'' <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> said. `` What they'll basically do is what has worked best in the past for specific models. The prime interest rate rose by half a percentage point Monday to 10.5 percent at major <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> banks. The prime rate is what banks charge their best customers to borrow money, and the new rate means consumers will pay more to finance a new car. `` If a dealer offers a guy an $ 800 rebate on a new car and he goes to the bank and finds out the interest rate is 13 \ percent, the buyer may walk away,'' <PERSON> Phillippi </PERSON> said `` It might be smarter to say ` The car costs this much. We'll give it to you at 7.9 percent interest.'''
