<HEAD>Engineering Firms Settle in WPPSS Trial; One Defendant Remains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two engineering firms that designed two abandoned <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Public Power Supply System nuclear power plants have agreed to a $ 25 million cash settlement to get themselves out of the WPPSS securities fraud trial. <PERSON> Junius </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>, a court-appointed settlement master in the case, announced the settlement Monday as the trial resumed in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Court here. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Constructors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ebasco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> agreed to pay $ 14.8 million and $ 7.2 million, respectively, to former <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> bondbuyers who bought into <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION>' proposal in the late 1970s to build two nuclear power plants in western <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. New York-based <ORGANIZATION> Ebasco </ORGANIZATION> also will pay up to $ 3 million in cash if the plaintiffs recover less than that in disputed claims against <ORGANIZATION> Ebasco </ORGANIZATION>'s insurance carriers. In addition, <ORGANIZATION> Ebasco </ORGANIZATION> agreed to surrender part of at least $ 50 million in disputed insurance claims that the company may recover. A class of 24,000 plaintiffs sued more than 100 original defendants after <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> defaulted in 1983 on $ 2.25 billion in municipal bonds sold to build the plants. The plaintiffs claim <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION>, 88 public utility districts, and others conspired to lie and hide information that might have discouraged investors. Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> signed an order severing <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ebasco </ORGANIZATION> from the suit, leaving <ORGANIZATION> Blyth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Webber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the securities firm that acted as financial adviser to <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION>, as the only remaining defendant in the case. Including the latest settlement, the original defendants have agreed to pay about $ 675 million plus funds recovered from insurance claims. <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> still must approve the settlements. He has not yet scheduled hearings on approval testimony. Plaintiff attorney <PERSON> Mel </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> called the settlement `` a fair compromise of our claims.'' He said he was taking into account the previous settlements and `` the desire to get money to our clients as quickly as possible.'' <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> said he no longer was talking with <PERSON> Blyth </PERSON> <PERSON> Eastman </PERSON> attorneys about settlement possibilities. After the jury was reseated for the first time in more than a week, he instructed members to attach no significance to settlement talk. As he had done when two earlier settlements were announced, he did not tell the jury the provisions of the agreement between the engineering firms and the plaintiff. Testimony resumed with <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> employee <PERSON> Harlan </PERSON> `` <PERSON> Hank </PERSON><PERSON> '' </PERSON> <PERSON> Kosmata </PERSON>'s 24th trial day on the witness stand Plaintiff attorney <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON> asked Kosmata why several issues were not included in bond-sale documents called official statements, which were given to potential bond investors. <LOCATION> Kosmata </LOCATION>, the liaison with the utilities in the project, rejected <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON>'s suggestions that concerns about how construction budgets were compiled might have been of interest to potential investors. He said the important issue was that the budgets were approved, not that `` preliminary'' concerns about them were expressed. <PERSON> Kosmata </PERSON> also reaffirmed earlier testimony that he heard no one suggest presenting test litigation in court to see if the utilities had authority to commit themselves to the project. That authority was lacking, the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled in 1983, and the agreements to pay off the bonds could not be enforced. That ruling led to the bond default. <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON> introduced a 1983 affidavit of <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, an attorney for Bonners Ferry -LRB- <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> -RRB- Municipal Utility, saying the issue of test litigation regarding the authority was discussed at a May 1975 meeting before the utilities agreed to the project. <PERSON> Kosmata </PERSON> said he attended that meeting and heard no discussions about a test case. `` I came away with a firm feeling there was no problem,'' he said.
