<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> stockholders are facing another moment of reckoning, either to sell their shares and make a windfall profit or to sit tight for the next unpredictable chapter in history's biggest corporate takeover battle. A company-imposed deadline for a second round of multibillion-dollar bids to buy the food and tobacco conglomerate was scheduled to expire at 5 p.m. today, and no decisions were expected before Wednesday. Speculation that new, fatter offers would emerge pushed <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION>'s stock price up $ 1 a share Monday to $ 89, more than 50 percent above its value before the takeover saga began two months ago. The stock rose another 87 -LCB- cents by late this morning in heavy trading. At least two of the three known bidders _ an <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> management group and the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> _ were working on revised proposals, according to people familiar with the bidding process. There was no indication Monday whether the third contender, a group led by the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, planned to alter its bid, which in the first round was considered the riskiest but potentially the richest. A special committee of <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION>'s outside directors, conducting the auction for the nation's 19th largest industrial company, declined comment on whether any additional bidders had emerged. But officials of Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> had said previously that the