<SECOND>BC-Cropland Paved, Adv 03-04,0687</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 03</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Dec. 3-4 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Houses, Malls Encroach on California Croplands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VISALIA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The problems of attorney <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Dooley </PERSON>, who farms a small parcel east of here, show how difficult it's getting to balance the interests of agriculture and development in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Residents in the area complain about dust, noise, bugs and traffic congestion caused by slow-moving tractors, while farmers suffer from vandalism to farm and irrigation equipment and trash from weekend picnickers. Repeated complaints by neighbors finally forced <PERSON> Dooley </PERSON> to change his cropping patterns. `` We just do n't grow cotton on our ranch anymore. The conflicts are just too severe,'' he said. Rapid growth in the fertile <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Joaquin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, locked between <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, may eventually ruin farming in what is regarded as the world's richest agricultural region. A <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> study shows as many as 50,000 acres of productive crop land in the state are paved over or removed from production each year because of urbanization. Air pollution primarily brought on by heavy vehicle traffic is making serious cuts in production of some crops, such as grapes, according to <LOCATION> Fresno </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Supervisor <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON>, a panelist at a recent discussion here sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` We can preserve the land, but if we ca n't preserve the production, what good is it?'' <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON> said of the air pollution issue. `` If we do n't do some planning and take care of some of the obvious shortfalls, it's going to be too late.'' About 815,000 acres of farm land will be lost in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> between now and the year 2000, estimated <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Williamson </PERSON>, a former assemblyman who sponsored the state's strong farmland conservation measures in the early 1960s. `` All efforts now being made are inadequate for the purpose of protecting farm land,'' <PERSON> Williamson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> Shafroth </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farmland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION>, agreed that current preservation efforts are inadequate but said public officials have a number of tools available to spare crop lands from a layer of fresh asphalt. <PERSON> Shafroth </PERSON> called for strict land-use regulations to prevent `` leap-frog'' development, or housing subdivisions and industrial parks situated in the middle of productive fields. Such development in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Natomas </LOCATION> area of <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> has led to the demise of once-productive rice farms. <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, planning and development director for <LOCATION> Tulare </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, said planners must regard agriculture as an industry when examining housing development proposals. `` Just as locating a residence in an industrial park leads to conflict and does not make sense, locating a residence in the middle of an agricultural area does not make sense,'' said <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>. `` Rural residential growth right now in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Joaquin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> is the greatest threat to preservation of farm land,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. The practice of splitting off small parcels of the farm so family members can build homes or `` rural ranchettes'' is a common way development encroaches on agriculture, he said. <PERSON> Dooley </PERSON> said his farm ca n't use certain chemicals because of the nearby homes, and the materials he does use can only be applied by ground spray rigs, not by aerial cropdusters. To keep developers at bay, farmers are being encouraged to retain their land when inflated prices make selling out a lucrative option. The sale of development rights to public agencies is another option. Under such agreements, a public agency pays a farm owner the difference between the farm land's current and potential value for housing or other urban uses. When development rights are conveyed, future development is restricted in the property deed, but the farmer retains ownership of the land. A similar concept is used to acquire land in the <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tahoe </LOCATION> basin to stop excessive development and improve environmental quality. While financing such a program is unclear, officials have suggested such options as bond issues, taxes on sales of converted farm land, or local taxing districts.
</TEXT>
