<HEAD>Honeywell To Sell Colorado Semiconductor Operation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday it plans to sell its semiconductor operation in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, Colo. The <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> unit manufactures custom and semi-custom integrated circuits for the computer merchant market, as well as for <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>'s internal needs and select military customers. `` The decision to sell the <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> operation is consistent with our desire to concentrate on our core businesses,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Renier </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> president and chief executive officer. `` With the divestiture of the computer business at the end of 1986 and actions since then to focus on our leadership position in controls, we no longer need such an extensive facility for circuits used internally, nor is it in our strategic interest to be in the merchant chip business,'' <PERSON> Renier </PERSON> added. `` Except for highly proprietary circuits, most of our semiconductor needs can be satisfied on the outside,'' he said. The <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> operation is part of the company's <ORGANIZATION> Solid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION>, which also includes a research and development facility in <LOCATION> Plymouth </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> had previously said it intended to restructure the division to fit the company's strategic direction. <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> said it would maintain the Plymouth facility as a modest captive operation. It will transfer a limited number of fabrication technologies and products from <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Plymouth </LOCATION> to aid in meeting future internal and military customer requirements for proprietary integrated circuits. The company is seeking a buyer who will also continue to support external customers and also <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>'s internal requirements during a transition period. About 1,100 employees work in the four-building <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> complex and <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> said it expects employees to transfer to the new owner at the time of sale.
