<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Fall</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar retreated against most major currencies in European trading Tuesday, buffeted by a lower-than-expected growth rate for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy. Gold prices also slipped. Currency dealers said a revision of the third-quarter <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> gross national product _ the broadest measure of economic health _ to 2.6 percent from 2.2 percent prompted dollar selling. Most traders said they had anticipated growth of at least 3 percent during the July-September period. The British pound, however, remained strong. The currency was helped by last week's boost in bank base interest rates by one percentage point to 13 percent. Dealers said Monday's increase by major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks of their prime lending rates, to 10.5 percent from 10 percent, was n't a sufficient incentive for the markets to switch from pounds to dollars. British rates are now the highest of all leading Western economies, making the pound one of the more attractive currencies. Dealers said the British central bank intervened to sell some pounds for dollars Tuesday in an attempt to slow sterling's gain. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, one British pound cost $ 1.8425, more expensive for buyers than Monday's $ 1.8385. Other late rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> compared with Monday's late rates: 1.7285 West German marks, down from 1.7332; 1.4481 Swiss francs, down from 1.4515; 5.9125 French francs, down from 5.9225; 1.9530 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9547; 1,281.25 Italian lire, down from 1,285.50; and 1.1930 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1918. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar closed at 122.15 Japanese yen, up from 122.00. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> the dollar traded lower at 121.65 yen. Gold bullion prices were around a dollar lower in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> after rising earlier in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the major European trading center for the precious metal, gold closed at $ 422.75 a troy ounce, down from $ 423.85. The Zurich closing price was $ 422.25 an ounce, down from $ 423.25. <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> gold closed at a bid $ 423.31 an ounce, up from $ 422.02. Silver bullion traded late in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at $ 6.09 a troy ounce, down from $ 6.16.
