<HEAD>Steel Output Rose 2.7 Percent in Week Ended Nov. 26</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Steel production rose to 1.832 million tons in the week ended Nov. 26, an increase of 2.7 percent from the previous week's 1.783 million tons, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> reported. The industry's production amounted to 85.4 percent of capacity during the week, compared with 83.2 percent in the previous week, the <ORGANIZATION> AISI </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. Estimated figures for the year to date showed production at 90.201 million net tons, an increase of 14.3 percent from the 78.939 million net tons in the previous year. Production so far this year used 89.1 percent of capacity, compared with 77.9 percent a year earlier. Net tonnage by district for the week ended Nov. 26: <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, 268,000; <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, 179,000; <LOCATION> Youngstown </LOCATION>, 100,000; <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Erie </LOCATION>, 167,000; <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, 158,000; <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, 467,000; <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, 171,000; Southern, 230,000; and Western, 92,000.
