<FIRST>r f AM-ConstructionContracts     11-29 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Construction Contracts,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says October Construction Contracts Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release after 5:30 p.m. EST; time set by source</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New construction contracts rose slightly in October after a three-month slump, on the strength of residential building everywhere except in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION>, a business-research company reported Tuesday. The F.W. <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said that new construction projects last month were up 1 percent to an annualized value of $ 240.2 billion. Construction contracts fell 3 percent in September, following drops in the previous two months. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION> economist, said that while the October improvement was welcome, it `` should be interpreted as a pause rather than a turnaround for the sagging construction sector.'' `` The prospect of a post-election rise of interest rates presents the risk of a further setback for this credit-sensitive industry,'' <PERSON> Christie </PERSON> said. `` Housing, which provided most of October's support, is especially vulnerable.'' Housing starts were up by about 7 percent in October, with the value of contracts for one - and multi-family houses rising 4 percent to an annualized $ 120.8 billion, the report said The report said that all regions shared in the improved housing activity but the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION>, which experienced a 10 percent decline from September's rate of contracting. October contracting for nonresidential buildings fell 8 percent to an annualized $ 75.6 billion, the report said. It said the biggest declines were in office buildings, down 23 percent, and in schools, down 22 percent. For the first 10 months, new construction starts on an unadjusted basis totaled $ 213.4 billion, down 3 percent from the same period in 1987, the report said. The South, with a shortfall of 6 percent, remained the nation's weakest building market in 1988, while the West held even with last year, it said.
</TEXT>
