<FIRST>u f AM-Takeovers-Profits Bjt   11-29 0744</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Takeovers-Profits, Bjt,0768</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shareholder Windfalls From Megadeals: Where Will All That Money Go?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Billions of dollars in potential shareholder profits from two staggering takeover deals have aroused a debate over how the money will be reinvested, with some strategists saying the outcome could determine the future direction of stocks and the economy. In one of the biggest takeovers ever, <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION> will buy <ORGANIZATION> Kraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> for $ 12.6 billion or $ 106 a share. For owners of <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON> shares prior to the takeover plan _ first disclosed last month, when the stock traded at about $ 60 _ that represents a profit of more than 76 percent. An even bigger deal looms for <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which has been the target of competing bids valued at between $ 21.3 billion to $ 26.8 billion, or $ 94 a share to $ 118 as share. For holders of <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> shares, which traded at about $ 56 in mid-October, that means a potential maximum profit of nearly 111 percent. If a significant part of the money from the megadeals is plowed back into the stock market, it would be considered a strong sign of confidence that the country is growing and recession is unlikely for a while. On the other hand, if most of the money goes into interest-bearing accounts or government bonds, it will reinforce fears that stocks will head lower and an economic downturn is n't far off. `` My opinion is the stock market is in a major peak,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> LaLoggia </PERSON>, author of Special Situation Report, a widely followed market newsletter based in <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> `` My advice, to anybody lucky enough to own stock in a takeover target taken out in a peak, is to put it to work in a <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bill,'' <PERSON> LaLoggia </PERSON> said. A few optimists have predicted that because of the sheer volume of this money, some will find its way into the stock market and could serve as the octane to drive up prices, perhaps snapping Wall Street out of its slump. But the prevailing view appears to be that most shareholders _ the majority of them large institutional investors _ likely will park their profits in safe, short-term government <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds. The 8.3 percent yield of a three-month <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bill represents a better investment than components of the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500-stock index, a widely watched barometer of the general stock market's health, which has risen about 8.7 percent the entire year `` With interest rates moving up, and three-month <ORGANIZATION> Treasuries </ORGANIZATION> yielding more than 8 percent, it's hard to justify giving up that safety for the risk of the stock market,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Blitzer </PERSON>, chief economist for <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` That suggests to me that whoever owns shares in whatever celebrated buyout is going on, if he listens to most investment advisers, he wo n't put it back into the stock market,'' <PERSON> Blitzer </PERSON> said. `` He'll wait for a sunnier day.'' Countering this view is the theory that while demand for stocks continues, the number of stocks is shrinking, partly because of takeovers and mergers such as the <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> deals. According to Federal Reserve figures, the amount of available stock has shrunk by about $ 75 billion in each of the past two years. If that's true, some strategists say, simple laws of supply and demand will dictate that stock prices rise, making them more attractive and drawing more investors _ including those who made windfall profits in the two big takeovers. `` I would assume part of that money would be going into the stock market,'' said <PERSON> Rao </PERSON> <PERSON> Chalasani </PERSON>, a market strategist at the Cleveland-based firm <ORGANIZATION> Prescott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ball </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Turben </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` I think there are other stocks priced similarly to those two companies prior to when the takeovers were announced,'' he said. `` Some of the money would go into these companies, regardless of whether they will be taken over.'' Others say the supply-demand theory is a fiction promoted by the securities industry when it's clear the stock market has hit a cyclical high. `` I regard all the work I've seen that says there's a supply-demand situation to be nonsense,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Cramer </PERSON>, owner of <ORGANIZATION> Cramer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> money management firm. `` The main reason is, you can buy all the GE you want, you can buy all the <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> you want, and the prices are n't rising,'' he said. `` There are too many stocks that nobody wants and too few that everybody wants.''
</TEXT>
