<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, in his final budget, will make one last effort to overhaul the way <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> parcels out money, including recommending a switch from 1-year to 2-year spending plans, administration sources said Tuesday. Officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the president will submit a laundry list of recommended changes in the way the appropriations process works. Many of these proposals are ones that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has sought repeatedly during his White House tenure, such as presidential authority to veto individual items in appropriations bills and a constitutional amendment requiring a balanced budget. While <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will leave office without getting any of his pet reforms adopted, advisers to President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> have indicated that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will pursue the fight for at least some of the changes. Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, who will stay on in the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration, has been particularly supportive of the 2-year budget cycle. `` The planning for the federal government is so hectic that if we can get it on a 2-year basis we would greatly improve the process and I think that many in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> feel the same way,'' <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> has said. Currently, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> must review agencies' requests for funds each year and pass a spending plan for the budget year, which begins Oct. 1. The deliberations consume hundreds of hours for lawmakers, who often miss the start of the fiscal year and are forced to pass a stopgap spending measure to keep the government from shutting down. In his State of the Union address last January, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> called for a switch to a 2-year budget cycle, proposing that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> try the approach on a trial basis covering defense spending for two years. The effort was short-circuited, however, when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the administration were forced to enter budget summit negotiations late last year following the collapse of the stock market. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has encountered stiff opposition in the past to his ideas for budget reform, primarily because many of them involve shifting power from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to the president. But some officials suggested that with a new administration and the urgent need to deal with the budget deficit, it was possible that reforming the budget process would gain momentum. Many are looking to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, a high-level advisory panel on the deficit, to take the lead in recommending ways to streamline the budget process. Several members of the commission, including former <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Caspar </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON>, have said they believe reforming the process should be a top priority in any deficit-reduction plan. According to sources, these are the proposals the president is expected to make on Jan. 9 when he sends his final budget to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>: _ 2-YEAR BUDGET CYCLE <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has said that a 2-year budget would eliminate repetitive annual budget tasks, give <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> more time for oversight functions and eliminate budgetary gimmicks, such as shifting spending from one year into the next to make the deficit appear smaller. _ LINE ITEM VETO The president has repeatedly sought the same power `` that 43 governors have'' to veto individual items in a spending bill without having to reject the entire bill. The veto could be overridden by a two-thirds vote in both houses. _ BALANCED BUDGET AMENDMENT Another <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> perennial, this constitutional amendment would require revenues and spending to be in balance, similar to requirements in effect in many states. Along with this, the president also supports a constitutional amendment to require a greater-than-majority vote whenever <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> raises taxes. _ JOINT RESOLUTION Currently, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> passes a joint resolution early in the budget process that provides the broad outlines for spending and taxes, but this proposal is not subject to presidential review. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> wants a change to require the president's signature on the resolution as a way of involving the executive branch in the process. _ PRESIDENTIAL CUTS The president under current law must ask <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for permission if he decides not to spend money the lawmakers appropriate. The request, known as a `` rescission,'' however, can simply be ignored by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, forcing the president to go ahead and spend the money. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> wants to require <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to go on record with an up-or-down vote each time a president asks for authority not to spend money. _ INDIVIDUAL SPENDING BILLS <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is supposed to appropriate money through 13 separate spending bills but occasionally ends up passing a catchall bill with up to two-thirds of the government's spending crammed into one massive document For the first time since 1976, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was able to get all 13 spending bills passed this year. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would like stiffer rules to make <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> live up to this requirement.
</TEXT>
