<HEAD>Fujitsu To Make Big Payment To IBM For Software Information</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 11th graf, IBM's stock ..., with 1 graf to UPDATE with
closing stock price; picks up 12th graf, The companies ....</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY31</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> will pay <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> $ 237 million in the next two weeks and millions more in coming years in return for secrets about the software that runs <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> mainframe computers, arbitrators said Tuesday. The arbitrators' binding order ends a bitter dispute that began in 1982, when <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> accused <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION> of copying the complex base-layer software that runs <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s most powerful computers. The arbitrators, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mnookin </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, compensated <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> for the information it must surrender while removing doubt about the legality of compatible software developed by <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION>. `` The arbitrators, Solomon-like, solved a dilemma in that both sides get what they want,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Geran </PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION> Both companies issued written statements expressing satisfaction with the order but were forbidden by the arbitrators from commenting further. Analysts said the amount of money being paid to the world's largest computer company was less important than the affirmation of its property rights and the limits on information <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION> can obtain `` <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> came out ahead on the arbitration. What <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> gave up was limited, and they got back a nice sum of money,'' said <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Soundview </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s biggest computer maker, has already paid $ 471 million to <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> under a defunct 1983 accord and $ 125 million as partial payment for a paid-up license covering future use of previously released <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION> programs, some of which contain <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> programming material In addition to the $ 237 million that remains to be paid on the paid-up license, <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION> will make annual payments each year through June 25, 1997, for use of new <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> programming material. The arbitrators will decide how big the payments will In 1989, the fee will be between $ 26 million and $ 51 million. By the end of the century, <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION>'s overall payments to <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> could exceed $ 1 billion. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s stock rose 50 cents a share to $ 119.37 -LCB- Tuesday in consolidated <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading, after rising $ 2.87 -LCB- a share Monday on anticipation of the announcement. The announcement was made after the close of Tuesday's trading of <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION> stock in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. The companies reached a private settlement in 1983, but the vaguely worded agreement fell apart and <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> in 1985 asked to have the dispute settled by binding arbitration. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arbitration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> gave the case to <PERSON> Mnookin </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> law professor, and <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, a retired computer expert from <ORGANIZATION> Norfolk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The men announced a preliminary agreement in September 1987. In addition to specifying payments, the arbitrators' new order spells out the ground rules under which <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION> engineers may examine <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> software in a secure location that will be set up in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION> makes computers and base-layer software that are intended to run the same programs as the mainframe computers made by <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>. However, slight discrepancies in the two companies' base-layer software, known as the operating system, mean that <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION>'s computers have not been entirely compatible with <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s The arbitrators' order will give <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION> enough information so that <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION> computers and base software should be able to run all <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> mainframe software without modification. But <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION> will still have to do its own programming. `` <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION> ca n't just take a reel of tape from <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, copy it and send it out to all their customers,'' <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said. The arbitrators decided <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION> deserved the inside information from <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> out of fairness to <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION> customers and to the company itself, which began copying <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s base software at a time when its legal property status was unclear. <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION>'s mainframe computers are sold mainly in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, where some are marketed by <ORGANIZATION> Siemens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Hitachi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Amdahl </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> company that is partly owned by <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION>, also compete in the market for IBM-compatible mainframes. But they do not produce their own base software. Customers of those companies buy their operating system software from <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Gens </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, predicted that <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION> would continue to do battle before the arbitrators on interpretation of the terms of the order. Protracted battles would hurt <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION>, which needs to get information as quickly as possible to stay current with <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>. The arbitrators will have jurisdiction over the companies' interactions through Nov. 29, 2002.
