<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Fall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar dropped sharply and then recovered most of its ground Tuesday in a confused session dominated by speculation about the direction of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates. The dollar declined after the government reported an upward revision in the third-quarter <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> gross national product to 2.6 percent from 2.2 percent. Some traders said the dollar fell because the market had been anticipating growth of closer to 3 percent during the July-September period. Others said the growth was healthy and did not account entirely for the dollar's drop. The dollar's rise, which picked up momentum in the early afternoon in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, appeared to be unrelated to any economic news, traders said. Some big banks may have bid the dollar up in an effort to put a squeeze on `` shorts'' _ that is, traders who had borrowed dollars in hopes that the currency would decline and they would be able to make a profit by paying back the lenders with cheaper dollars, said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pugh </PERSON>, vice president for foreign exchange at <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` It caught a lot of people by surprise,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyman </PERSON>, senior corporate foreign-exchange dealer for the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Traders were looking ahead to Friday's report on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> unemployment in November, which could give a hint about the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s future monetary policy. Traders have chosen to focus in recent weeks on the outlook for interest rates in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Tighter monetary policy would push up short-term <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates, making dollar-denominated securities more attractive to investors. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, one British pound cost $ 1.8425, more expensive for buyers than Monday's $ 1.8385. Later in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the pound rose to $ 1.8443 from $ 1.8399 Monday. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar closed at 122.15 Japanese yen, up from 122.00. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> the dollar traded lower at 121.65 yen. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the dollar fell to 121.83 yen from 122.28 yen Monday. Other late rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with Monday's late rates, included: 1.7348 West German marks, down from 1.7355; 1.4500 Swiss francs, down from 1.4524; 1.1913 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1931; 5.9310 French francs, up from 5.9273; and 1,282.50 Italian lire, down from 1,286.25. Other late rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with Monday's late rates, included: 1.7285 West German marks, down from 1.7332; 1.4481 Swiss francs, down from 1.4515; 5.9125 French francs, down from 5.9225; 1.9530 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9547; 1,281.25 Italian lire, down from 1,285.50; and 1.1930 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1918. Gold prices rose in Asian trading but fell later in the day in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold closed at a bid of $ 423.31 an ounce, up from $ 422.02. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the major European trading center for the precious metal, gold closed at $ 422.75 a troy ounce, down from $ 423.85. The closing price in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, was $ 422.25 an ounce, down from $ 423.25. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold bullion for current delivery fell to $ 421.90 a troy ounce from $ 423.30. Later, <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> said gold bullion was bid at $ 421.50 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, down from $ 422.10 late Monday. Silver bullion traded late in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at $ 6.09 a troy ounce, down from $ 6.16. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex, silver bullion for current delivery fell to $ 6.030 a troy ounce from $ 6.113 late Monday.
