<HEAD>Sugar Rallies On Supply Fears, Technical Factors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Sugar futures prices surged Tuesday on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Coffee, <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> despite a lack of fresh news, a sign of the market's increasing concern about the possibility of a supply shortage, analysts said On other markets, grains and soybeans finished mostly higher; energy futures were mixed; precious metals were lower; livestock and meat were mixed; and stock-index futures advanced. Sugar for delivery in March settled .33 cent higher at 11.30 cents a pound, the contract's highest close since Aug. 8, which also was the last day March sugar closed above 11 cents. During Tuesday's session, the March contract traded as high as 11.33 cents a pound, challenging the previous day's intra-day peak of 11.34 cents, a four-month high. Since falling below 9 cents a pound in late September, sugar futures have risen fairly steadily on indications that world sugar production in the current crop year may fall short of consumption, reducing already-low inventories to critical levels. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> all are rumored to be looking for more sugar in the September-through-August crop year, yet <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> reportedly has asked <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to accept deferred delivery of scheduled shipments, analysts said. Last week, the West German statistics firm F.O. Licht reduced its estimate of this year's European sugar-beet crop by 750,000 metric tons, increasing fears of a production defict instead of the surplus that had been expected only a few months ago. `` There have been concerns that if there is a sudden increase in demand from the physical market, the sugar might not be available. Now that there's the possibility of a production deficit, those concerns are being felt even more strongly,'' said <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Ganes </PERSON>, a sugar market analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Analyst <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> said technical signals _ the chart patterns on which many speculators base their trading decisions _ were extremely bullish. Wheat, corn and soybean futures finished mostly higher on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> in a late flurry of buying by traders who had sold contracts earlier in the session. Analysts attributed the closing rally almost entirely to `` short-covering,'' a form of profit-taking that amounts to selling high, then buying low instead of buying low, then selling high. Oat futures plunged for the second straight day in a continuing reaction to abundant supplies of feed-quality oats, said <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Homan </PERSON>, an independent trader. <PERSON> Homan </PERSON> also said the oat market was shrinking away from the inflated prices caused by drought-related panic buying during the summer. Wheat settled 1 cent to 5 cents higher with December at $ 4.23 -LCB- a bushel; corn was -LCB- cent lower to 1 cent higher with December at $ 2.56 -RCB- a bushel; oats were 5 cents to 9 -LCB- cents lower with December at $ 1.95 -LCB- a bushel; soybeans were -LCB- cent to 4 \ cents higher with January at $ 7.53 -RCB- a bushel Energy futures settled mixed on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as the markets began consolidating the sharp gains of recent sessions. After the close of trading, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> released figures showing a 2.7 million-barrel drawdown in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude-oil stocks and a 2.5-million-barrel decline in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> gasoline stocks last week. Stocks of petroleum distillates increased by 1.76 million barrels, according to the API. Crude futures were expected to open higher Wednesday in reaction to the report. West Texas Intermediate crude settled 11 cents lower to 15 cents higher with January at $ 14.92 a barrel; heating oil was .86 cent lower to .80 cent higher with December at 47.79 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .01 cent lower to .70 cent higher with December at 46.87 cents a gallon. Intra-day weakness in crude prices, coupled with the weakness of the dollar pressured precious-metals futures on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Savaiko </PERSON>, a metals analyst with <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Gold settled 50 cents to $ 1.40 lower with December at $ 421.90 a troy ounce; silver was 8.5 cents to 9 cents lower with December at $ 6.03 a troy ounce. On the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, live cattle settled .10 cent to .47 cent lower with December at 73.10 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .25 cent higher with January at 82.70 cents a pound; hogs were .35 cent lower to .45 cent higher with December at 39.47 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .05 cent to .13 cent lower with February at 43.05 cents a pound. Stock-index futures advanced moderately on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where the contract for December delivery of the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500 settled 2.20 points higher at 271.15. The contract is worth $ 500 a point.
