<HEAD>Government Charges GE with Defrauding Army of $10 Million</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: DELETES 11th graf pvs, The Army... as unnecessary. SUBS
penultimate graf to DELETE redundant reference to May 1985.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and two employees were indicted Tuesday on federal charges of hiding $ 10 million worth of savings in a contract to make a battlefield computer system. GE, the nation's third-largest defense contractor, said the indictment was `` unfair'' and `` sensationalized,'' adding that the company intends to fight the charges. GE also said an internal investigation showed pricing discrepancies totaling $ 3.69 million, which the company already has refunded. GE faces a maximum penalty of $ 71.871 million plus restitution, the government said. `` We look forward to the opportunity to have a jury judge the merits of the case,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, first assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney. The defense case was not the first involving GE. In 1985, the company pleaded guilty to unrelated contract-fraud charges. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said no decisions have been made as yet on suspension or debarment of <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> to bid on defense contracts. `` The allegations will now have to be reviewed by the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Caldwell </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. The 321-count indictment charges that <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION>, through its wholly-owned subsidiary <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in King of <LOCATION> Prussia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, negotiated subcontracting costs less than anticipated and hid the lower prices from the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. GE was awarded a $ 250 million contract in June 1983 to make the `` decentralized automated service support system'' for the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. The company and the two employees lied to the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> about the prices the company was paying for parts and raw materials and double-billed for some materials, according to the indictment. The government also charges <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Badolato </PERSON>, 41, of <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, formerly the subcontracts manager for <LOCATION> MATSCO </LOCATION>, with trying to cover up the scheme by altering dates of purchase orders and withholding information from government auditors. The other employee, <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leo </PERSON>, 51, of King of <LOCATION> Prussia </LOCATION>, formerly the materials manager for MATSCO, was also charged with lying to a federal auditor. In its statement, <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> denied any criminal wrongdoing and said the employees maintained their innocence. <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> and <PERSON> Badolato </PERSON> referred reporters to the company attorneys. `` The simple fact is that the case against <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> revolves around a negotiaion in the spring of 1983 in which the two employees at <ORGANIZATION> MASCO </ORGANIZATION> allegedly failed to notify the Army that they had succeeded in negotiating lower subcontract prices with several vendors than had originally been projected,'' <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> said in a written statement. `` Any legitimate governmental interest could be served by an appropriate civil resolution of this matter,'' <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> said. GE is charged with five counts of mail fraud and 312 counts of presenting false claims to the government. <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> was charged with racketeering, five counts of mail fraud and two counts of making false statements and concealing material facts from a federal agency. <PERSON> Badolato </PERSON> was charged with one count of racketeering, five counts of mail fraud, one count of obstructing agency proceedings and one count of making false statements and concealing material facts from a federal agency. <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> and <PERSON> Badolato </PERSON> have since been transferred to other parts of <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION>, the government said. In 1987, <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> did $ 5.8 billion worth of business with the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, the government said. If convicted, <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> faces a maximum of 55 years in jail, $ 1.276 million in fines and forfeiture of salary bonuses and company stock derived from the racketeering. <PERSON> Badolato </PERSON> faces the same penalties plus $ 5,000 more in fines if convicted. <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harbist </PERSON>, assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney said he did not know the amount of bonuses the men received. GE pleaded guilty in May 1985 to contract-fraud charges, paying a $ 1.04 million fine and rembursing the government $ 800,000. The company was indicted in March 1985 for forging employee time cards and manipulating costs to recover losses on the Minuteman missles.
