<HEAD>Church's Obtains Further Order Against Popeyes Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge on Tuesday ordered Popeyes Famous Fried Chicken to make further disclosures before it may buy stock of <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fried </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicken </ORGANIZATION> under its $ 290 million hostile buyout offer. Separately, Church's board of directors met in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and authorized management to explore alternatives to Popeyes' $ 8 a share tender offer, including a possible transaction with a third party. <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>, Texas-based Church's, the nation's second-biggest fried chicken chain, rejected Popeyes' offer as inadequate on Oct. 25, and again on Tuesday. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON> issued a preliminary injunction barring Popeyes from buying <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>'s stock until 10 business days after it makes certain disclosures regarding its alleged use of non-public corporate information. Church's has contended that its former chief financial officer, <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kilbourne </PERSON>, took confidential inside corporate information with him when he was hired by New Orleans-based Popeyes, the nation's No. 3 chicken chain. Church's also contened Popeyes financial adviser, <PERSON> Wasserstein </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Perrella </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, relied on that information in formulating the takeover bid. <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON> ordered Popeyes: to reveal the information on which its buyout offer was made and to stop using, at least for now, any confidential Church's information it might have. The judge also ordered Popeyes to disclose the amount of money the company had spent to buy and maintain an offshore racing boat, corporate jet, helicopter, yacht, bus and luxury car used by its chairman, <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Copeland </PERSON>. On Monday, <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON> issued a temporary restraining order forbidding Popeyes from pursuing the buyout until similar disclosures were made. A Church's spokesman said the company would appeal the judge's refusal to grant a permanent injunction against the takeover and a preliminary injunction on the antitrust claims <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON>, Popeyes' <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> lawyer, said <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON> would have all the information this week. He said he could not comment on the claim that Popeyes' offer was based on insider information. Regarding the corporate expenditures for boats, planes and other conveyances, <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> said: `` All those expenses have been treated as legitimate business expenses by the business firm retained by Mr. <PERSON> Copeland </PERSON> and been reviewed very carefully.''
</TEXT>
